# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bbc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] A general strike took place in the United Kingdom from 4 to 12 May 1926.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It was called by the General Council of the Trades Union Congress (TUC) in an unsuccessful attempt to force the British government to act to prevent wage-reductions and worsening conditions for 1.2 million locked-out coal miners.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Some 1.7 million workers went out, especially in transport and in heavy industry.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It was a sympathy strike, with many of those who were not miners and not directly affected striking to support the locked-out miners.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] As well as workplace stoppages other organisation included 'Councils of Action, food distribution, and support for picket lines in some places.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The government was well prepared, and enlisted middle- and upper-class volunteers to maintain essential services.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] There was little violence and the TUC gave up in defeat.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] From 1914 to 1918, the United Kingdom participated in World War I.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Heavy domestic use of coal during the war depleted once-rich seams.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Britain exported less coal during the war than it would have in peacetime, allowing other countries to fill the gap.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] This particularly benefited the strong coal industries of the United States, Poland, and Germany.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In the early 1880s, coal production was at a peak of 310 tons per man annually, but in the four years preceding the war, this amount had fallen to 247 tons.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] By the 1920–1924 period, this had fallen further to just 199 tons.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Total coal output had been in decline since 1914 as well.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In 1924, the Dawes Plan was implemented.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It allowed Germany to re-enter the international coal market by exporting "free coal" to France and Italy, as part of their reparations for the war.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In 1925, Winston Churchill, the chancellor of the Exchequer, reintroduced the gold standard.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] This made the British pound too strong for effective exporting to take place from Britain.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Furthermore, because of the economic processes involved in maintaining a strong currency, interest rates were raised, which hurt some businesses.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Mine owners wanted to maintain profits even during times of economic instability, and to do so they reduced wages for miners in their employment.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Miners' weekly pay had been lowered from £6 to £3 18*s.* over seven years.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Owners eyed increasing working hours too.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] When mine owners announced their intention to reduce miners' wages further, the Miners' Federation of Great Britain rejected the terms: "Not a penny off the pay, not a minute on the day." The Trades Union Congress responded by promising to support the miners in their dispute.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The Samuel Commission published its report on 10 March 1926, recommending that national agreements, the nationalisation of royalties, and sweeping reorganisation and improvement should be considered for the mining industry.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It also recommended a reduction of 13.5% of miners' wages, along with the withdrawal of the government subsidy.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Two weeks later, the prime minister announced that the government would accept the report if other parties also did.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] A previous royal commission, the Sankey Commission in 1919, had failed to reach an agreement, producing four different reports with proposals ranging from complete restoration of private ownership and control, to complete nationalisation.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] David Lloyd George, the then prime minister, offered reorganisation, which was rejected by the miners.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Following the Samuel Commission's report, the mine owners declared that miners would be offered new terms of employment including lengthening the work day and reducing wages depending on various factors.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The Miners' Federation of Great Britain refused the wage reduction and regional negotiation.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The final negotiations began on 1 May but failed to achieve an agreement, leading to an announcement by the TUC that a general strike "in defence of miners' wages and hours" was scheduled to begin on Monday, 3 May, at one minute to midnight.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The leaders of the Labour Party were troubled about the proposed general strike because they were aware of the revolutionary elements within the union movement and of the damage that they might do to the party's new reputation as a party of government.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] During the next two days, frantic efforts were made to reach an agreement between the government and the mining industry representatives.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] However, they failed, mainly because of an eleventh-hour decision by printers of the *Daily Mail* to refuse to print an editorial ("For King and Country") condemning the general strike.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] They objected to the following passage: "A general strike is not an industrial dispute.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It is a revolutionary move which can only succeed by destroying the government and subverting the rights and liberties of the people".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Baldwin was now concerned about the TUC and printers' action interfering with the freedom of the press.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The Communist Party of Great Britain cooperated with the Trades Union Congress in rallying and organizing the strike.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The TUC feared that an all-out general strike would bring revolutionary elements to the fore and limited the participants to railwaymen, transport workers, printers, dockers, ironworkers, and steelworkers, as they were regarded as pivotal in the dispute.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In a rare political radio broadcast, Archbishop Francis Cardinal Bourne, the leading Catholic prelate in Britain, condemned the strike, knowing that many strikers were Catholic.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] He advised that "It is a direct challenge to lawfully constituted authority. ...
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It was ready and able to do whatever it could to keep the country moving.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It rallied support by emphasizing the revolutionary nature of the strikers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The armed forces and volunteer workers helped maintain basic services.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The government used the Emergency Powers Act 1920 to maintain essential supplies.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 4 May 1926, the number of workers on strike was estimated at between 1½ million and 1¾ million.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] There were strikers "from John o' Groats to Land's End".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The reaction to the strike call was immediate and overwhelming, surprising both the government and the TUC; the latter not being in control of the strike.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On this first day, there were no major initiatives and no dramatic events except for the nation's transport being at a standstill.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 5 May 1926, both sides gave their views.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Churchill commented as editor of the government newspaper *British Gazette*: "I do not agree that the TUC have as much right as the Government to publish their side of the case and to exhort their followers to continue action.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It is a very much more difficult task to feed the nation than it is to wreck it".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Baldwin wrote, "The general strike is a challenge to the parliament and is the road to anarchy".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The *British Worker*, the TUC's newspaper, wrote: "We are not making war on the people.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] We are anxious that the ordinary members of the public shall not be penalized for the unpatriotic conduct of the mine owners and the government".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In the meantime, the government put in place a "militia" of special constables called the Organisation for the Maintenance of Supplies (OMS) of volunteers to maintain order in the street.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] A special constable said: "It was not difficult to understand the strikers' attitude toward us.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] After a few days I found my sympathy with them rather than with the employers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] For one thing, I had never realized the appalling poverty which existed.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] If I had been aware of all the facts, I should not have joined up as a special constable".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It was decided that fascists would not be allowed to enlist in the OMS without first giving up their political beliefs, as the government feared a right-wing backlash so the fascists formed the so-called "Q Division" under Rotha Lintorn-Orman to combat the strikers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 6 May 1926, there was a change of atmosphere.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The government newspaper, *British Gazette*, suggested that means of transport into London began to improve compared to the first day with volunteers, car sharing, cyclists, private buses, as well as strikebreakers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] A statement on the front page indicated 200 London General Omnibus Company buses 'on the streets'.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Only 86 LGOC buses, however, were operating.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 7 May 1926, the TUC met Samuel and worked out a set of proposals designed to end the dispute.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The Miners' Federation rejected the proposals.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The *British Worker* was increasingly difficult to operate, as Churchill had requisitioned the bulk of the supply of the paper's newsprint so it reduced its size from eight pages to four.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In the meantime, the government took action to protect the men who decided to return to work.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 8 May 1926, there was a dramatic moment on the London Docks.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] They broke the picket line and transported food to Hyde Park.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] That showed that the government was in greater control of the situation.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] It was also a measure of Baldwin's caution, in place of Churchill's more reactionary stance.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Churchill had wanted, in a move that could have proved unnecessarily antagonistic to the strikers, to arm the soldiers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Baldwin, however, had insisted otherwise.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In Plymouth, tram services were restarted, with some vehicles attacked and windows smashed.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] However, not all strike actions in the city were confrontational; a football match, attended by thousands, occurred between a team of policemen and strikers, with the strikers winning 2–0.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The supporters included a delegation of 4,000 strikers, which marched to the grounds accompanied by a marching band.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 9 May 1926, George Kidwell, secretary of the 'San Francisco Bakery Wagon Drivers' Union' sent a cable to Ben Tillett, leader of the dockers union congratulating them and other workers on a 'wonderful demonstration of working-class power'.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 10 May 1926, the *Flying Scotsman* was derailed by striking miners at Cramlington, a short distance north of Newcastle upon Tyne.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The *British Worker*, alarmed at the fears of the General Council of the TUC that there was to be a mass drift back to work, claimed: "The number of strikers has not diminished; it is increasing.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] There are more workers out today than there have been at any moment since the strike began".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] However, the National Sailors' and Firemen's Union applied for an injunction in the Chancery Division of the High Court to enjoin the General-Secretary of its Tower Hill branch from calling its members out on strike.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Mr Justice Astbury granted the injunction by ruling that no trade dispute could exist between the TUC and "the government of the nation" and that except for the strike in the coal industry, the general strike was not protected by Trade Disputes Act 1906.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] In addition, he ruled that the strike in the plaintiff union had been called in contravention of its own rules.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] As a result, the unions involved became liable, at common law, for incitement to breach of contract and faced potential sequestration of their assets by employers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] On 12 May 1926, the TUC General Council visited 10 Downing Street to announce its decision to call off the strike if the proposals worked out by the Samuel Commission were respected and the government offered a guarantee there would be no victimization of strikers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The government stated that it had "no power to compel employers to take back every man who had been on strike".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] However, the TUC agreed to end the dispute without such an agreement.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Various strikes continued after this as their unions negotiated deals with companies for their members to return to work.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The TUC's decision to call off the strike unconditionally, without input from those striking or winning any guarantees or improvements, lead to criticism and feelings of betrayal from workers and weakened unions, as well as victimization of the strikers as they returned to work.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The miners maintained resistance for a few months before being forced by their own economic needs to return to the mines.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] By the end of November, most miners were back at work.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] However, many remained unemployed for many years.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Those still employed were forced to accept longer hours, lower wages, and district wage agreements.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The effect on British coal mines was profound.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] By the late 1930s, employment in mining had fallen by more than a third from its pre-strike peak of 1.2 million miners, but productivity had rebounded from under 200 tons produced per miner, to over 300 tons by the outbreak of the Second World War.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The split in the miners that resulted from Spencerism and the agreement of the Nottinghamshire miners to return to work, against the policy of the Miners' Federation of Great Britain, divided the coal miners as a national bargaining force until the establishment of the National Union of Mineworkers.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The Trade Disputes and Trade Unions Act 1927 banned sympathy strikes, general strikes, and mass picketing, creating a system whereby trade union members had to 'opt-in' to paying the political levy to the Labour Party.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Following the strike, the TUC and trade union movement remained intact and did not change their basic policies.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Keith Laybourn says that historians mostly agree that "In no significant way could the General Strike be considered a turning point or watershed in British industrial history." Trade union membership, on the other hand, reduced substantially and the unions were weakened.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] There have been no further general strikes in Britain.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Union leader Ernest Bevin, who had coordinated the strike, considered the strike a mistake; he decided that action by political parties was a better solution.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] Rank and file workers, however, felt betrayed by the TUC.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] An issue of the *Worker's Bulletin* published around the time the TUC called off the strike described the decision to call it off as "the greatest crime that has ever been permitted ... against the working class of Great Britain".
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] The country came close to a one-day general strike on 31 July 1972 over the imprisonment of the Pentonville Five.
[src:bbc/1926-united-kingdom-general-strike] There was a general strike amongst loyalists in Northern Ireland in 1974.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Central Television became Ostankino Television, and the First Program of Central Television became known as Channel 1 Ostankino.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company "Ostankino" was entrusted with the function of covering political, cultural and economic life in the CIS member states.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Yegor Yakovlev became the Chairman of the State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] At the initial stage, there were few changes compared to the last years of the existence of the Soviet Central Television.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The news program was Novosti, and the information and analytical program was Itogi with Yevgeny Kiselyov.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The channel's logo was a stylized image of a unit enclosed in a square.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Since 1992, the socio-political talk show "Tema" with Vladislav Listyev, the analytical talk show "Red Square" with Alexander Lyubimov and the program "Politburo", hosted by Alexander Politkovsky began to be broadcast.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The producer of these programs was the television company VID.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The main problem of the activities of the State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino was the "spread" of advertising among thematic studios, which began during the existence of the USSR State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In 1990–1991, three thematic studios received the status of legal entities, including the Experiment studio, which was the main customer for the production of television programs at JSC VID Television Company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] At the beginning of 1992, instead of almost all other thematic main editorial offices of Central Television, thematic studios of the State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino were created; for example, ITA had its own advertising department.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Some of the studios paid private television organizations for the programs produced to their order with their advertising time.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The Main Advertising and Commercial Directorate itself was created only in May 1993; the Ostankino Advertising Agency, which operated before that, only placed advertising between programs.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In the summer of 1992, Eduard Sagalaev created MNVK, which took over the evening of 6 TVK in Moscow (from 1993 to 1994, economic and educational programs of the Severnaya Korona television company were broadcast on Channel 6 in the morning and afternoon).
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Instead of Eduard Sagalaev, Igor Malashenko, who had previously been its political director, became the general director of the television and radio company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In the fall of 1992, Russian businessmen founded the OITV company in Israel, which since the fall of 1993 has been retransmitting the signal of one of the belt versions of 1st channel Ostankino abroad.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In particular, such a version of the channel was broadcast in Israel itself, in early February 1994 in Transnistria, for some time in Ukraine, and from the beginning of 1994 in some cities in the European part of Russia.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Israeli Russian- and English-language advertising was broadcast on Ostankino International Television, sometimes blocking the broadcasts.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The exact fate of OITV is unknown: presumably, it stopped broadcasting after the launch of ORT, in April–May 1995.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On October 4, 1992, the broadcast of George Lucas's film Star Wars was removed from the air with the wording "pirated film purchased for showing without film and video rights".
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] This was the first removal from the air on domestic television.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The space saga was shown on Channel One only 13 years later, in 2005, with stereo sound.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On November 24, 1992, Yegor Yakovlev was dismissed due to the showing of a film about the war between Ingushetia and North Ossetia–Alania.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On January 11, 1993, Vyacheslav Bragin was appointed Chairman of the Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company "Ostankino".
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Due to disagreements over the methods of managing the television and radio company, Igor Malashenko left the post of General Director, and his place was taken by Oleg Slabynko.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Under the leadership of Bragin and Slabynko, the channel began to work more often in the interests of Boris Yeltsin, while state censorship began to strengthen.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] ITA editor-in-chief Oleg Dobrodeev and host of the Itogi program Yevgeny Kiselyov considered it impossible to work under the current conditions and, together with Igor Malashenko and businessman Vladimir Gusinsky, founded the NTV television company, which took over production of the Itogi program.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] From the fall of 1993 to the spring of 1994, Ostankino experienced a large outflow of ITA journalists and employees of some other departments, who transferred to the staff of NTV Television Company LLC.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] At the same time, many employees of the television and radio company began to leave for the new channel TV-6, created by the former head of the television and radio company Eduard Sagalaev.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] After this, only Channel Five and RTR remained on the air, which broadcast Vesti every half hour, and also retransmitted a live CNN broadcast.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On October 4 at 6:30 the broadcast was resumed, and footage of the siege was shown on Teleutra, as well as a live broadcast of the storming of the White House.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] After these events, Vyacheslav Bragin demanded that security be strengthened at the buildings of the television and radio company's editorial offices and studios.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On December 16, 1993, Vyacheslav Bragin resigned from the post of chairman of the Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] This position was initially offered to Vladimir Mukusev, but due to his conflict with the television company's staff, this candidacy was withdrawn.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] This position was also offered to Yevgeny Kiselyov, but he refused.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Alexander Yakovlev was appointed chairman, and Oleg Tochilin was appointed editor-in-chief of the Information Television Agency.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] By February 1994, Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company and All-Russia State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company had accumulated debt to state-owned communications enterprises: as of January 1, 1996, they amounted to 412 billion rubles.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The employees of Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company saw the solution in the creation of trading houses controlled by the television and radio company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Since October 1992, the commercial Russian-language television channel Orsent TV has been broadcasting on the frequencies of the Ostankino 1st Channel in Estonia at night, after the channel's broadcasts have ended.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In 1993–1994, this channel's broadcasts were conducted from 5 to 6 p.m., thus, the broadcasts of Ostankino in Estonia at this time were overlapped by Orsent TV programs.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] According to the concluded agreement, the channel could broadcast on the air of LitPollinter TV for only a few hours.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On February 6, 1995, the LitPollinter TV channel stopped broadcasting due to financial problems, and the 1st Ostankino Channel in Lithuania began broadcasting in pure form again (however, on April 1 it was replaced by ORT, and on May 5 ORT transferred the frequency to the LNK channel).
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Initially, the channel was of an informational and artistic nature.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The weekday program consisted of news, popular science, cultural and educational, documentary programs, one-part television films and mini-series, distributed under the headings "Homebody", "Third Age" and "Children's Hour".
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] However, due to the reduction in expenses on state television, which occurred in an earlier period, the channel reduced the number of programs prepared and television films produced.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Over time, they were replaced by entertainment programs, which were produced mainly by private television organizations.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Some airtime was given over to showing domestic and foreign films, combined into several sections (for example, In the Detective Club on Fridays from September 4, 1992).
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] As a result of all this, the volume of production of domestic television films fell sharply, and the production capacities of the Studio Ekran and the Television Technical Center began to stand idle.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In late 1992 and early 1993, the television game show for teenagers, Star Hour and the children's television game show, Call of the Jungles, as well as the program, When Everyone is Home also appeared.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On September 19, 1993, the program "Itogi" was broadcast for the last time.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Then, from October 10, 1993, it began to be broadcast on Channel 5, and from January 23, 1994 - on Channel 4, part of whose airtime was taken up by the NTV television company.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Instead of the program "Itogi", information and analytical programs "Voskresenye" with Sergei Alekseev and "Novosti Plus" with Sergey Medvedev began to be broadcast.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In 1994, a new wave of expansion of the number of programs produced by private television organizations on the air occurred.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Since May 1994, the topical interview show "Rush Hour" has been aired on weekdays, hosted by Vladislav Listyev; the producer of this program was the television company "VID", and the program was aired daily in prime time, at 19:10.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The host of the program Tema was Lidiya Ivanova.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The program "Red Square" also resumed its broadcast under the old name "Vzglyad", hosted by Alexander Lyubimov, and six months before that, the program "Politburo" resumed its broadcast.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Cultural and educational programs began to be aired in prime time - So That They Remember" and "Silver Ball".
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Since the end of 1993, talk shows produced by the ATV television company began to be broadcast on Mondays: We and If, hosted by Vladimir Pozner, and A Man and a Woman with Kira Proshutinskaya.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In certain periods, private television organizations produced up to 70% of television programs, excluding news, films and archival recordings.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Since July 4, 1994, due to the cutback in funding for Ostankino State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company and the need to reduce the broadcasting time of 1st channel Ostankino to 12 hours, a technical break was added to the channel's weekday program from 11:20 to 16:00.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] GMS took on the compilation of a program digest, on the basis of which Igor Krutoy's firm ARS, commissioned by the television company, produced the television program Compass GMS.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Advertising placement was subordinated to GMS's own advertising agency.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The GMS weekday program usually consisted of 8-minute news releases every hour, two repeat showings of feature films (since October 1994 - one film) and some kind of cultural, educational or entertainment program.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] By the beginning of September, it became available in twelve more cities in Russia, while in the remaining cities there was a break in broadcasting during the daytime.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] At the same time, in some neighbouring countries, the channel did not broadcast at all due to the peculiarities of time zones.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] A new broadcasting schedule was adopted on October 3, 1994: from now on, news releases were broadcast at the 52nd minute of each hour, overlapping programs that were broadcast at that time, the timing of each news release was 8 minutes (such a broadcasting schedule initially existed on GMS).
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The Vremya programs (as the 21:00 news broadcasts were again called in December 1994) were not affected by these changes.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] At the end of 1994, RGTRK Ostankino demanded that non-state television companies "share" some of their prime time, which meant closing some of the programs of non-state television companies.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Then the television companies "VID", "ATV", "REN-TV" and "Klass!" created the Association of Independent Television Producers, which came up with the initiative to create Public Russian Television (ORT), the majority of whose shares would belong to various business representatives.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Broadcasting on Channel 1 Ostankino was supposed to go to it.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] This joint-stock company was given the right to place advertising on the channel.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] RGTRK Ostankino did not receive any dividends for 1994 from the holding, and the holding's debt to the television and radio company as of July 1, 1995 amounted to 19.0 billion rubles.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] According to the initial proposal, 15% each belonged to the private television organizations Television Company VID, ATV, Television Company REN-TV, and RTV-Press, 20% to the bankers, and 20% to the state.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] This joint-stock company was founded at its all-Russian constituent meeting of shareholders on January 24, 1995.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Vladislav Listyev was appointed General Director of ORT, Badri Patarkatsishvili and Kirill Ignatyev were appointed his first deputies, and the chairman of the board of directors of ORT was the chairman of the Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino, Alexander Yakovlev.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] ORT broadcasting was originally planned to begin on February 1, 1995.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] A decision was also made to introduce a moratorium on advertising from March 1.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] But on the evening of that very day, Listyev was killed in the entrance to his own home three hours after the Rush Hour program.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On March 20, Sergei Blagovolin became General Director of ORT.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Its director was Midkhat Shilov, who had previously been responsible for literary and artistic editing.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On April 1, 1995, the channel's frequencies were transferred to ORT.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] News broadcasts, as before 1994, began to be broadcast on the usual schedule, at 9:00, 12:00, 15:00, 18:00 and after midnight with a duration of 20 minutes.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The announcer service was abolished (now announcers did not work on camera).
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Daytime breaks were also excluded from the broadcasting grid (retained in some subjects of the Russian Federation), while JSC "GMS" did not disappear from the air - it continued to broadcast under the ORT logo.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] For a short time, the television and radio company became the producer of a number of programs, series and cycles.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Among them were: the next season of the TV series "The Little Things of Life", meetings with Alexander Solzhenitsyn, "Play, My Favorite Accordion!", etc.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In addition, its area of responsibility included organizing sports broadcasts and providing Soviet feature films and animated films for reruns.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The information television agency continued to produce news for the ORT television channel, the Vremya program, the morning channel Teleutro, and the final analytical television magazine "Sunday".
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] The main socio-political talk show of ORT was the program One on One (TV program), hosted by Alexander Lyubimov, and the hosts of the program "Rush Hour" were Sergei Shatunov and Dmitry Kiselev [228].
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] Many programs that survived from the times of either the RGTRK "Ostankino" or the Central Television of the USSR were closed already during the active work of ORT.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] On October 6, 1995, the decree of the president of Russia on the liquidation of the Russian State Television and Radio Broadcasting Company Ostankino was published, after which on October 12 it was finally liquidated by a decree of the Government of Russia.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] In March 1996, ITA was liquidated, and the staff involved in providing Ostankino television coverage was laid off, fired, or integrated into the staff of ORT or other channels.
[src:bbc/1st-channel-ostankino] At the same time, some former ITA employees, such as Oleg Tochilin and Yulia Rakcheeva, transferred to the NTV television company.
[src:bbc/1xtra] According to RAJAR, the station broadcasts to a weekly audience of 786,000 with a listening share of 0.3% as of March 2024.
[src:bbc/1xtra] BBC Radio 1Xtra's music includes largely British, North American, Caribbean and African hip-hop, rap, grime, drill, trap, jungle, UK garage, dubstep, drum and bass, UK funky, house, R&B, soul, urban, gospel, dancehall, soca, reggae, Afrobeats, amapiano and bhangra.
[src:bbc/1xtra] It is available on BBC Sounds, digital radio (DAB) and digital television.
[src:bbc/1xtra] The first ever track played on 1Xtra was a specially created track produced by DJ Skitz and Rodney P and featuring Beverley Knight and Blak Twang.
[src:bbc/1xtra] The five-hour show was presented by the Rampage DJ collective and the station's then breakfast show host, KC.
[src:bbc/1xtra] As part of its public service broadcasting remit, 1Xtra is required to carry a significant amount of news, information and speech content.
[src:bbc/1xtra] 1Xtra had its own news service, 1Xtra News (formerly known as "TX"), which was operated as a subsidiary of Radio 1's Newsbeat operations.
[src:bbc/1xtra] The tone and style of the news presentation is in keeping with the station's overall target audience - young and predominantly urban.
[src:bbc/1xtra] Initially, in addition to regular hourly bulletins, TX had a flagship weekday two-hour news, features and discussion show under the title "TX Unltd" (pronounced "Unlimited").
[src:bbc/1xtra] This show - initially broadcast in a 5 pm – 7 pm slot - rated poorly, however, and was later absorbed into a mixed music-and-speech format (similar to that used by Jeremy Vine on Radio 2) which aired in mid-afternoon (2 pm – 4 pm) and was named after its host, Max.
[src:bbc/1xtra] The Trust required that 1Xtra's main bulletins not air at the same time as those on Radio 1.
[src:bbc/1xtra] When the new bulletins were introduced in late summer 2009, they aired at noon and 5 pm, with Radio 1's bulletins remaining at 12:45 pm and 5:45 pm.
[src:bbc/1xtra] As of Summer 2009 it was reported that Radio 1 and 1Xtra were carrying shared news bulletins at weekends; weekday news output remained separate.
[src:bbc/1xtra] September 2012 saw a substantial increase in Newsbeat bulletins simulcast with Radio 1.
[src:bbc/1xtra] Weekday breakfast bulletins at 6 am, 7.30 am, 8 am, 8.30 am and 9.30 am remain bespoke 1Xtra broadcasts.
[src:bbc/1xtra] From 10:30 am, bulletins are shared with Radio 1, including the 15-minute Newsbeat magazines at 12:45 pm and 5:45 pm.
[src:bbc/1xtra] In the first quarter of 2011, 1Xtra was part of an efficiency review conducted by John Myers.
[src:bbc/1xtra] In November 2017, reports signalled that the Roundhouse Rising concert series would partner with 1Xtra.
[src:bbc/1xtra] As part of the change, the BBC curated a free grime night in the venue's Sackler Space.
[src:bbc/1xtra] BBC Radio 1Xtra's typical audience is between fifteen and thirty years old.
[src:bbc/1xtra] Weekday evening shows began with MistaJam helming a three-hour multi-genre show, followed by six hours of specialist output tailored to a particular genre (e.g.
[src:bbc/1xtra] (The Saturday 4 am replay of Target's Friday night show was also axed, to make room for Bright's sixth show) This has now itself been replaced by a rerun of the previous week's overnight mix show from 4 am to 6 am, giving nine hours of specialist output.
[src:bbc/1xtra] Weekday overnights (1 am – 3 am), Saturday overnights (1 am – 4 am) and Saturday evenings (7 pm – 1 am) are now simulcast entirely with Radio 1 - this allows Radio 1's flagship urban content to air on 1Xtra.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The **2003 invasion of Iraq** was the first stage of the Iraq War.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion began on 20 March 2003 and lasted just over one month, including 26 days of major combat operations.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion was conducted by a United States-led coalition of mainly American, British, Australian, and Polish troops.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush and UK prime minister Tony Blair, the coalition aimed to disarm Iraq of weapons of mass destruction (WMDs)—nuclear, chemical, and biological weapons—and "free the Iraqi people" by deposing president Saddam Hussein, in turn ending his "support for terrorism".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Before the invasion, United Nations (UN) inspectors in Iraq had found no evidence of Iraqi WMDs; U.S. and British officials claimed they were still hidden, and posed an immediate threat to world peace.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion was strongly opposed by some long-standing U.S. allies, including Canada, France, Germany, and New Zealand.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2004, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan called the invasion illegal under international law, as a breach of the UN Charter.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 15 February 2003, there were worldwide protests against the anticipated invasion of Iraq, including a rally of three million people in Rome which was the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion began with an airstrike on the Presidential Palace in Baghdad on 20 March 2003.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The following day, coalition forces launched an incursion into Basra Governorate from their massing point close to the Iraqi–Kuwaiti border.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While special forces launched an amphibious assault from the Persian Gulf to secure Basra and the surrounding petroleum fields, the main invasion army occupied southern Iraq, engaging in the Battle of Nasiriyah on 23 March.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Massive air strikes across the country and against Iraqi command and control threw the defending army into chaos and prevented an effective resistance.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 26 March, the 173rd Airborne Brigade was airdropped near the northern city of Kirkuk, where they joined forces with Kurdish rebels and fought several actions against the Iraqi Army, to secure the northern part of the country.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The main body of coalition forces continued their drive into the heart of Iraq and were met with little resistance.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Most of the Iraqi military was quickly defeated.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 9 April 2003, 22 days after the first day of the invasion, the capital city of Baghdad was captured by coalition forces after the six-day-long Battle of Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other operations included the capture and occupation of Kirkuk on 10 April and the attack on and capture of Tikrit on 15 April.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam and the Iraqi central leadership went into hiding, as the coalition forces finished occupying the country.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 1 May, Bush declared the "end of major combat operations" in Iraq; this began the occupation phase of the Iraq War, in which coalition forces fought the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam was captured by U.S. forces on 13 December 2003.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Gulf War began in 1990, and ended in 1991 with a ceasefire between the United Nations coalition and Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. and its allies tried to keep Saddam Hussein in check with military actions such as Operation Southern Watch, by monitoring and controlling some Iraqi airspace, as well as using economic sanctions.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Violating the Biological Weapons Convention, Iraq's biological weapons (BW) program began in the early 1980s, with help from the U.S. and European countries reportedly unaware of Iraq's intentions.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Details of Iraqi biological and chemical weapons program surfaced after the Gulf War, following investigations by the UN Special Commission (UNSCOM), which had been charged with the post-war disarmament of Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The investigation concluded that the program had not continued after the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraqi military helicopters and planes regularly contested the no-fly zones.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 1998, regime change in Iraq became official U.S. foreign policy with enactment of the Iraq Liberation Act, enacted following the expulsion of UN weapons inspectors months earlier (some had been accused of spying for the U.S.).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] One month later, the U.S. and UK bombed Iraq during Operation Desert Fox, their rationale being to hamper Iraq's ability to produce chemical, biological, and nuclear weapons, but U.S. intelligence personnel also hoped it would help weaken Saddam's grip on power.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush's inauguration in January 2001, the U.S. moved towards a more aggressive policy toward Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Republican Party's 2000 campaign platform called for the U.S. to "remove" Saddam.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After leaving the Bush administration, Treasury Secretary Paul O'Neill said that an attack on Iraq had been planned since Bush's inauguration, and that the first U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] National Security Council meeting involved discussion of an invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] O'Neill later backtracked, saying that these discussions were part of a continuation of foreign policy first put into place by the Clinton administration.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Despite the Bush administration's stated interest in invading Iraq, little formal movement towards an invasion occurred until the 11 September attacks (9/11).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On the morning of 11 September 2001, the al-Qaeda militant organization, led by Osama bin Laden, committed four coordinated terrorist attacks on the U.S., using hijacked commercial airliners to crash into major symbols of American economic and military power.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Messages intercepted by the National Security Agency during the attacks pointed to al-Qaeda's responsibility for them.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] By mid-afternoon, however, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld ordered the Pentagon to prepare plans for attacking Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to aides near him that day, Rumsfeld messaged: "Best info fast.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Judge whether good enough hit S.H. [Saddam Hussein] at same time.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 12 September, Bush ordered White House counter-terrorism coordinator Richard A.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Clarke to investigate possible Iraqi involvement in 9/11.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Shocked by the sophistication of the attacks, the administration wondered whether a state sponsor was involved.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Clarke's office issued a memo on 18 September that noted wide ideological gaps between Iraq and al-Qaeda, and that only weak anecdotal evidence linked the two.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, U.S. vice president Dick Cheney and Rumsfeld expressed skepticism toward's the CIA's intelligence.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They questioned whether the CIA were competent enough to produce accurate information as the agency underestimated threats and failed to accurately predict events such as the 1979 Iranian Revolution, the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, and the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They instead preferred outside analysis, of which information was supplied by the Iraqi National Congress as well as unvetted pieces of intelligence.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This information alleged that a highly secretive relationship existed between Saddam and al-Qaeda from 1992, specifically through a series of meetings reportedly involving the Iraqi Intelligence Service (IIS).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The rationale for invading Iraq as a response to 9/11 has been widely questioned, as there was no cooperation between Saddam and al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 20 September 2001, Bush addressed a joint session of Congress (telecast live to the world), and announced his new "war on terror".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This announcement was accompanied by the doctrine of "pre-emptive" military action, later termed the Bush Doctrine.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 21 November, Bush spoke with Rumsfeld and instructed him to conduct a confidential review of OPLAN 1003, the war plan for invading Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Rumsfeld met with General Tommy Franks, the commander of U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Central Command (CENTCOM), on 27 November to go over the plans.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A record of the meeting includes the question "How start?", listing multiple possible justifications for a U.S.–Iraq War.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Some Bush advisers favored an immediate invasion of Iraq, while others advocated building an international coalition and obtaining UN authorization.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush eventually decided to seek UN authorization, while still reserving the option of invading without it.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Also that day, Benjamin Netanyahu testified before the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress, using expert testimony to encourage an invasion, and stating there was "no question" that Saddam was working on WMDs.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UK agreed with the U.S. actions, while France and Germany were critical of plans to invade Iraq, arguing instead for continued diplomacy and weapons inspections.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After considerable debate, the UNSC adopted a compromise resolution, UNSC Resolution 1441, which authorized the resumption of weapons inspections and promised "serious consequences" for non-compliance.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] UNSC members France and Russia made clear that they did not consider these consequences to include the use of force to overthrow the Iraqi government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Both the U.S. ambassador to the UN, John Negroponte, and the UK ambassador, Jeremy Greenstock, publicly confirmed this reading of the resolution, assuring that Resolution 1441 provided no "automaticity" or "hidden triggers" for an invasion without further consultation of the UNSC.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Resolution 1441 gave Iraq "a final opportunity to comply with its disarmament obligations" and set up inspections by the UN Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Saddam accepted the resolution on 13 November and inspectors returned to Iraq under the direction of UNMOVIC chairman Hans Blix and IAEA Director-General Mohamed ElBaradei.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As of February 2003, the IAEA "found no evidence or plausible indication of the revival of a nuclear weapons program in Iraq"; the IAEA concluded that certain items which could have been used in nuclear enrichment centrifuges, such as aluminum tubes, were in fact intended for other uses.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] UNMOVIC "did not find evidence of the continuation or resumption" of WMD programs, or significant quantities of proscribed items.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Shortly before the invasion, UNMOVIC stated that it would take "months" to verify Iraqi compliance with resolution 1441.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress passed the Iraq Resolution, which authorized the President to "use any means necessary" against Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Americans polled in January 2003 widely favored further diplomacy over an invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later that year, however, Americans began to agree with Bush's plan.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. government engaged in an elaborate domestic public relations campaign to market the war to its citizens.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Americans overwhelmingly believed Saddam did have WMDs: 85% said so, even though the inspectors had not uncovered those weapons.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Of those who thought Iraq had weapons sequestered somewhere, about half responded that said weapons would not be found in combat.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] By February 2003, 64% of Americans supported taking military action to remove Saddam from power.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the 2003 State of the Union address, Bush said "we know that Iraq, in the late 1990s, had several mobile biological weapons labs".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Secretary of State Colin Powell addressed the UNSC, continuing U.S. efforts to gain UN authorization for an invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] His presentation contained a computer-generated image of a "mobile biological weapons laboratory".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, this information was based on claims of Rafid Ahmed Alwan al-Janabi, codenamed "Curveball", an Iraqi emigrant living in Germany who later admitted that his claims had been false.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell falsely alleged that Iraq had ties to al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As a follow-up to the presentation, the U.S., UK, Poland, Italy, Australia, Denmark, Japan, and Spain proposed a resolution authorizing the use of force in Iraq, but Canada, France, Germany, and Russia strongly urged continued diplomacy.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Facing a losing vote as well as a likely veto from France and Russia; the aforementioned countries eventually withdrew their resolution.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Opposition to the invasion coalesced in the worldwide 15 February 2003 anti-war protest that attracted between six and ten million people in more than 800 cities, the largest such protest in human history.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 16 March 2003, Spanish Prime Minister José María Aznar, UK Prime Minister Tony Blair, Bush, and Prime Minister of Portugal José Manuel Durão Barroso as host met in the Azores to discuss the invasion of Iraq and Spain's potential involvement in the war, as well as the beginning of the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This encounter was extremely controversial in Spain, even now remaining a very sensitive point for the Aznar government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2004, Madrid suffered the worst terrorist attack in Europe since the Lockerbie bombing, motivated by Spain's decision to participate in the war, prompting some Spaniards to accuse the Prime Minister of being responsible.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In March 2003, the U.S., UK, Poland, Australia, Spain, Denmark preparing for the invasion of Iraq, with a host of public relations and military moves.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In his 17 March address to the nation, Bush demanded that Saddam and his two sons, Uday and Qusay, surrender and leave Iraq, giving them a 48-hour deadline.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UK House of Commons held a debate on going to war on 18 March where the government motion was approved 412 to 149.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The vote was a key moment in the history of the Blair administration, as the number of government MPs who rebelled against the vote was the greatest since the repeal of the Corn Laws in 1846.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Three government ministers resigned in protest at the war, John Denham, Lord Hunt of Kings Heath, and the then Leader of the House of Commons Robin Cook.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In December 2002, a representative of Iraqi General Tahir Jalil Habbush al-Tikriti, contacted former CIA Counterterrorism Department head Vincent Cannistraro, and stated that Saddam "knew there was a campaign to link him to 11 September and prove he had [WMDs]".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Cannistraro added that "the Iraqis were prepared to satisfy these concerns.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] I reported the conversation to senior levels of the state department and I was told to stand aside and they would handle it." Cannistraro stated that the offers made were all "killed" by the Bush administration because they allowed Saddam to remain in power, an outcome viewed as unacceptable.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It has been suggested that Saddam was prepared to go into exile if allowed to keep U.S.$1 billion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak's national security advisor, Osama El-Baz, sent a message to the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] State Department that the Iraqis wanted to discuss the accusations that the country had WMDs and ties with al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraq also attempted to reach the U.S. through the Syrian, French, German, and Russian intelligence services.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In January 2003, Lebanese-American Imad Hage met with U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Department of Defense official Michael Maloof.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Hage, a resident of Beirut, had been recruited by the department to assist in the war on terror.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He reported that Mohammed Nassif, a close aide to Syrian president Bashar al-Assad, had expressed frustrations about the difficulties of Syria contacting the U.S., and had attempted to use him as an intermediary.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Maloof arranged for Hage to meet with Richard Perle, then head of the Defense Policy Board.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In January 2003, Hage met with Iraqi intelligence official Hassan al-Obeidi.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Al-Obeidi told Hage that Baghdad did not understand why they were targeted and that they had no WMDs.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He then made the offer for Washington to send in 2000 FBI agents to confirm this.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He additionally offered petroleum concessions but stopped short of having Saddam give up power, instead suggesting that elections could be held in two years.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later, al-Obeidi suggested that Hage travel to Baghdad for talks; he accepted.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Later that month, Hage met with General Habbush and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] They also wished to meet with high-ranking U.S. officials.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 19 February, Hage faxed Maloof his report of the trip.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Maloof reports having brought the proposal to Jaymie Duran.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Pentagon denies that either Wolfowitz or Rumsfeld, Duran's bosses, were aware of the plan.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 21 February, Maloof informed Duran in an email that Richard Perle wished to meet with Hage and the Iraqis if the Pentagon would clear it.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Keep this close hold." On 7 March, Perle met with Hage in Knightsbridge, and stated that he wanted to pursue the matter further with people in Washington, D.C.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A few days later, he informed Hage that Washington refused to let him meet with Habbush to discuss the offer (Hage stated that Perle's response was "that the consensus in Washington was it was a no-go").
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Throughout 2002, the Bush administration insisted that removing Saddam from power to restore international peace and security was a major goal.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The principal stated justifications for this policy of "regime change" were that Iraq's continuing production of WMDs and known ties to terrorist organizations, as well as Iraq's continued violations of UNSC resolutions, amounted to a threat to the U.S. and the world community.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Bush, speaking in October 2002, said that "The stated policy of the United States is regime change. ...
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Bush administration's overall rationale for the invasion of Iraq was presented in detail by Powell to the UNSC.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In September 2002, Blair stated that "Regime change in Iraq would be a wonderful thing.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] That is not the purpose of our action; our purpose is to disarm Iraq of weapons of mass destruction..." In November of that year, Blair further stated that, "So far as our objective, it is disarmament, not regime change – that is our objective.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As Blair made clear in a statement to the House of Commons, "I detest his regime.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] But even now he can save it by complying with the UN's demand.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In September 2002, the Bush administration said attempts by Iraq to acquire thousands of high-strength aluminum tubes pointed to a clandestine program to make enriched uranium for nuclear bombs.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell referred to the tubes in his UNSC presentation.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A report released by the Institute for Science and International Security in 2002, however, reported that it was highly unlikely that the tubes could be used to enrich uranium.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Bush administration asserted that the Saddam government had sought to purchase yellowcake uranium from Niger.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 7 March 2003, the U.S. submitted intelligence documents as evidence to the International Atomic Energy Agency.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These documents were dismissed by the IAEA as forgeries, with the concurrence in that judgment of outside experts.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time, an American official stated that the evidence was submitted to the IAEA without knowledge of its provenance and characterized any mistakes as "more likely due to incompetence not malice".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the invasion, the U.S. government statements concerning Iraqi weapons programs and links to al-Qaeda have been discredited, though chemical weapons were found in Iraq during the occupation period.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While the debate of whether Iraq intended to develop chemical, biological, and nuclear weapons in the future remains open, no WMDs have been found in Iraq since the invasion despite comprehensive inspections lasting more than 18 months.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In Cairo, on 24 February 2001, Powell had predicted as much, saying, "[Saddam] has not developed any significant capability with respect to weapons of mass destruction.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Another justification included the alleged connection between Saddam's and that of terrorist organizations such as al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] While it never made an explicit connection between Iraq and 9/11, the Bush administration repeatedly insinuated a link, thereby creating a false impression for the U.S. public.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Grand jury testimony from al-Qaeda's 1993 World Trade Center bombing trials cited numerous direct connections between the bombers to Hussein's government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Iraqi National Congress alleged that Saddam had been collaborating with al-Qaeda since 1992 via the Iraqi Intelligence Service (IIS).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Steven Kull, director of the Program on International Policy Attitudes (PIPA), observed in March 2003 that the administration "has succeeded in creating a sense that there is some connection" between 9/11 and Saddam.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This was after a *New York Times*/CBS poll showed that 45% of Americans believed Saddam was "personally involved" in the attacks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] And we know that after September 11, Saddam Hussein's regime gleefully celebrated the terrorist attacks on America." The BBC noted the results of a recent poll which suggested that 70% of Americans believe Saddam "was personally involved" in 9/11.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the invasion, assertions of operational links between Iraq and al-Qaeda have largely been discredited by the intelligence community, and Powell himself later admitted he had no proof of it.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In October 2002, a few days before the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Powell suggested in his 2003 UN presentation that UAVs were transported out of Iraq and could be launched against the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In actuality, Iraq had no offensive UAV fleet or any capability of putting UAVs on ships.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Iraq's UAV fleet consisted of less than a handful of outdated Czech training drones.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time, there was a large dispute within the intelligence community whether the CIA's conclusions about the UAV fleet were accurate.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Air Force denied outright that Iraq had any offensive UAV capabilities.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Additional justifications used at various times included Iraqi violation of UN resolutions, the Iraqi government's repression of its citizens, and Iraqi violations of the 1991 ceasefire.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] As evidence supporting American and British claims about Iraqi WMDs and links to terrorism weakened, some supporters of the invasion have increasingly shifted their justification to the human rights violations of the Saddam government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002 was passed by Congress with Republicans voting 98% in favor in the Senate, and 97% in favor in the House.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Democrats supported the joint resolution 58% and 39% in the Senate and House respectively.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The resolution asserted the authorization by the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Constitution and Congress for Bush to fight anti-American terrorism.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Citing the Iraq Liberation Act, the resolution reiterated that it should be the policy of the U.S. to depose Saddam's government and promote a democratic replacement.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Armed Forces "as he determines to be necessary and appropriate", to "defend [American] national security ... against the continuing threat posed by Iraq".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The legality of the invasion of Iraq under international law has been challenged since its inception on a number of fronts, and several prominent supporters of the invasion in all the invading states have publicly and privately cast doubt on its legality.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It has been argued by the U.S. and UK that the invasion was fully legal because authorization was implied by the UNSC.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] International legal experts, including the International Commission of Jurists, a group of 31 leading Canadian law professors, and the U.S.-based Lawyers Committee on Nuclear Policy, have denounced this rationale.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] On 20 November 2003, *The Guardian* alleged that Richard Perle, a senior member of the administration's Defense Policy Board Advisory Committee, conceded that the invasion was illegal, but still justified.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The UNSC passed nearly 60 resolutions on Iraq and Kuwait since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Resolution 1441 was most prominent during the run-up to the war and formed the main backdrop for Powell's UNSC address.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the same time, U.S. officials advanced a parallel legal argument using the earlier resolutions, which authorized force in response to Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Under this reasoning, by failing to disarm and submit to weapons inspections, Iraq was in violation of UNSC Resolutions 660 and 678, and the U.S. could legally compel Iraq's compliance through military means.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In 2006, Luis Moreno Ocampo, the lead prosecutor for the International Criminal Court, reported that he had received 240 separate communications regarding the legality of the war, many of which concerned British participation in the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congressman Dennis Kucinich announced U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] House Resolution 333 and three articles of impeachment against Cheney.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] He charged Cheney with manipulating evidence for Iraqi WMDs, deceiving the public about Iraq's connection to al-Qaeda, and threatening aggression against Iran in violation of the UN Charter.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The original list prepared in March 2003 included 49 members.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Of those 49, only six besides the U.S. contributed troops to the invasion force (the UK, Australia, Poland, Spain, Portugal, and Denmark), and 33 provided some number of troops to support the occupation after the invasion was complete.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Six members have no military, meaning that they withheld troops completely.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Approximately 200,194 troops—148,000 American, 50,000 British, 2,000 Australian, and 194 Polish (GROM special forces)—were sent to Kuwait for the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The invasion force was also supported by Iraqi Kurdish Peshmerga fighters, estimated to number upwards of 70,000.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the latter stages of the invasion, 620 troops of the Iraqi National Congress opposition group were deployed to southern Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Canada discreetly contributed some military resources towards the campaign, such as personnel from the Royal Canadian Air Force who crewed American planes on missions in Iraq to train with the platforms, and eleven Canadian aircrew who manned AWACS aircraft.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Canadian official Eugene Lang stated that it was "quite possible" that Canadian forces indirectly supported the American operation.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to Lang, Canada's military strongly advocated to be involved in the Iraq War instead of the war in Afghanistan, and Canada mainly decided to keep its assets in the Gulf to maintain good relations with America.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] After the invasion, Canadian Brigadier General Walter Natynczyk served as Deputy Commanding General of the Multi-National Corps in occupied Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Plans to open a second front in the north were severely hampered when Turkey refused the use of its territory for such purposes.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In response to Turkey's decision, the U.S. dropped several thousand paratroopers from the 173rd Airborne Brigade into northern Iraq, a number significantly less than the 15,000-strong 4th Infantry Division that the U.S. originally planned to deploy to the northern front.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The number of personnel in the Iraqi military before the war was uncertain, but it was believed to have been poorly equipped.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The International Institute for Strategic Studies estimated the numbers: the Iraqi Armed Forces at 389,000 (Ground Forces 350,000, Air Force 20,000, Air Defense 17,000, and Navy 2,000), the paramilitary Fedayeen Saddam at 44,000, Republican Guard at 80,000, and reserves at 650,000.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] There were an estimated thirteen infantry divisions, ten mechanized and armored divisions, as well as some special forces units.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The Iraqi Air Force and Navy played a negligible role in the conflict.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] During the invasion, foreign volunteers traveled to Iraq from Syria and took part in the fighting, usually commanded by the Fedayeen Saddam.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] It is not known for certain how many foreign fighters fought in Iraq in 2003, however, intelligence officers of the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] First Marine Division estimated that 50% of all Iraqi combatants in central Iraq were foreigners.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In addition, the Kurdish Islamist militant group Ansar al-Islam controlled a small section of northern Iraq in an area outside Saddam's control.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam had been fighting against secular Kurdish forces since 2001.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] At the time of the invasion they fielded about 600 to 800 fighters.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam was led by the Jordanian-born militant Abu Musab al-Zarqawi, who would later become an important leader in the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Ansar al-Islam was driven out of Iraq in late March by a joint American-Kurdish force during Operation Viking Hammer.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In the information, the American forces provided the Dutch Ministry of Defense with the GPS coordinates of the DU rounds, along with a list of targets and numbers fired.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Then, the Dutch Ministry of Defence released the data to Dutch peace group Pax under the Freedom of Information Act.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Coalition forces used 61,000 cluster munitions containing 20 million submunitions during the Gulf War, and 13,000 cluster munitions containing two million submunitions during the 2003 invasion and subsequent insurgency.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Thousands of unexploded munitions from the invasion and previous wars, including cluster munitions, mines and other unexploded ordnance, still posed a threat to civilians as of 2022.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] CIA Special Activities Division (SAD) and MI6 (E Squadron) paramilitary teams entered Iraq in July 2002 before the 2003 invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Once on the ground they prepared for the subsequent arrival of American and British military forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Army Special Forces to organize the Kurdish Peshmerga.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This joint team combined to defeat Ansar al-Islam, an ally of Al Qaeda, in a battle in the northeast corner of Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A chemical weapons facility at Sargat was also captured.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Sargat was the only facility of its type discovered in the Iraq war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The U.S. side was carried out by Paramilitary Officers from SAD and the Army's 10th Special Forces Group.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] SAD teams also conducted high-risk special reconnaissance missions behind Iraqi lines to identify senior leadership targets.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These missions led to the initial strikes against Saddam Hussein and his key generals.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Although the initial strikes against Saddam were unsuccessful in killing the dictator or his generals, they were successful in effectively ending the ability to command and control Iraqi forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other strikes against key generals were successful and significantly degraded the command's ability to react to and maneuver against the U.S.-led invasion force coming from the south.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] SAD operations officers were also successful in convincing key Iraqi army officers to surrender their units once the fighting started or not to oppose the invasion force.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] NATO member Turkey refused to allow its territory to be used for the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Army Special Forces joint teams and the Kurdish Peshmerga constituted the entire northern force against government forces during the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Their efforts kept the 5th Corps of the Iraqi army in place to defend against the Kurds rather than moving to contest the coalition force in the south.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Four of these CIA officers were awarded the Intelligence Star for their actions.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] MI6 conducted Operation Mass Appeal which was a campaign to plant stories about Iraq's WMDs in the media and boost support for the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] MI6 also went on to bribe many of Saddam's closest allies to turn over information and intelligence.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to Tommy Franks, "April Fool", an American officer working undercover as a diplomat, was approached by an Iraqi intelligence agent.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] April Fool then sold the Iraqi false "top secret" invasion plans provided by Franks' team.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This deception misled the Iraqi military into deploying major forces in northern and western Iraq in anticipation of attacks by way of Turkey or Jordan, which never took place.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] This greatly reduced the defensive capacity in the rest of Iraq, and facilitated the actual attacks via Kuwait and the Persian Gulf in the southeast.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Since the Gulf War, the U.S. and UK had been attacked by Iraqi air defenses while enforcing Iraqi no-fly zones.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These zones, and the attacks to enforce them, were described as illegal by the former UN Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali, and the French foreign minister Hubert Vedrine.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Other countries, notably Russia and China, also condemned the zones as a violation of Iraqi sovereignty.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In mid-2002, the U.S. began more carefully selecting targets in the southern part of the country to disrupt the military command structure in Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] A change in enforcement tactics was acknowledged at the time, but it was not made public that this was part of a plan known as Operation Southern Focus.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The amount of ordnance dropped on Iraqi positions by coalition aircraft in 2001 and 2002 was less than in 1999 and 2000 which was during the Clinton administration.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] However, information obtained by the UK Liberal Democrats showed that the UK dropped twice as many bombs on Iraq in the second half of 2002 as they did during the whole of 2001.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The tonnage of UK bombs dropped increased from 0 in March 2002 and 0.3 in April 2002 to between 7 and 14 tons per month in May–August, reaching a pre-war peak of 54.6 tons in September – before the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Congress' 11 October authorization of the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] The 5 September attacks included a 100+ aircraft attack on the main air defense site in western Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] According to an editorial in *New Statesman* this was "located at the furthest extreme of the southern no-fly zone, far away from the areas that needed to be patrolled to prevent attacks on the Shias.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Tommy Franks, who commanded the invasion, has since admitted that the bombing was designed to "degrade" Iraqi air defences in the same way as the air attacks that began the Gulf War.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] These "spikes of activity" were, in the words of then-British Defence Secretary, Geoff Hoon, designed to 'put pressure on the Iraqi regime' or, as *The Times* reported, to "provoke Saddam Hussein into giving the allies an excuse for war".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] In this respect, as provocations designed to start a war, leaked British Foreign Office legal advice concluded that such attacks were illegal under international law.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] Another attempt at provoking the war was mentioned in a leaked memo from a meeting between Bush and Blair on 31 January 2003, in which Bush allegedly told Blair that "The U.S. was thinking of flying U2 reconnaissance aircraft with fighter cover over Iraq, painted in UN colours.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p01] If Saddam fired on them, he would be in breach." On 17 March, Bush gave Saddam 48 hours to leave the country, along with his sons Uday and Qusay, or face war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On the night of 17 March 2003, the majority of B and D squadron British 22nd SAS Regiment, designated as Task Force 14, crossed the border from Jordan to conduct a ground assault on a suspected chemical munitions site at a water-treatment plant in the city of al-Qa'im.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Following their insertion, D squadron established a patrol laager at a remote location outside al-Qa'im and awaited the arrival of B squadron, who had driven overland from Jordan.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Their approach to the plant was compromised, and a firefight developed which ended in one 'pinkie' having to be abandoned and destroyed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Repeated attempts to assault the plant were halted, leading the SAS to call in an air strike which silenced the opposition.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In the early morning of 19 March, U.S. forces abandoned the plan for initial, non-nuclear decapitation strikes against 55 top Iraqi officials, in light of reports that Saddam was visiting Uday and Qusay at Dora Farms, in the Dora farming community in southern Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At approximately 04:42 Baghdad time, two F-117 Nighthawk stealth fighters from the 8th Expeditionary Fighter Squadron dropped four enhanced, satellite-guided 2,000-pound GBU-27 'Bunker Busters' on the compound.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] One bomb missed the compound entirely, while the other three impacted the site on the other side of an electrified wall surrounding the main palace building, damaging it and destroying every other structure in the compound.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Saddam was not present, nor were any members of the Iraqi leadership.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Baghdad-area hospitals reported that the attack killed one civilian and injured fourteen others, including four men, nine women and one child.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Later sources indicated that Saddam had not visited the farm since 1995, while others claimed that Saddam *had* been at the compound that morning, but had left before the strike, which Bush had ordered delayed until the 48-hour deadline had expired.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Within seven hours, more than 70 sites were destroyed, effectively depriving the Iraqi military of any early warning of the coming invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] As the sites were eliminated, the first heliborne SOF teams launched from H-5 air base in Jordan, including vehicle-mounted patrols from the British and Australian components transported by the MH-47Ds of the 160th SOAR.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Ground elements of Task Force Dagger, Task Force 20, Task Force 14, and Task Force 64 breached the sand berms along the Iraqi border with Jordan, Saudi Arabia, and Kuwait in the early morning hours and drove into Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Unofficially, the British, Australians, and Task Force 20 had been in Iraq weeks prior.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 20 March at approximately 02:30 UTC, at 05:34 local time, explosions were heard in Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Special operations commandos from the CIA's Special Activities Division from the Northern Iraq Liaison Element infiltrated throughout Iraq and called in the early air strikes.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At 03:16 UTC, or 10:16 pm EST, Bush announced that he had ordered an attack against "selected targets of military importance" in Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] When this word was given, the troops on standby crossed the border into Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Before the invasion, many observers had expected a longer campaign of aerial bombing before any ground action, taking as examples the Gulf War or the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In practice, U.S. plans envisioned simultaneous air and ground assaults to incapacitate the Iraqi forces quickly which resulted in the shock and awe military campaign attempting to bypass Iraqi military units and cities in most cases.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The assumption was that superior mobility and coordination of coalition forces would allow them to attack the heart of the Iraqi command structure and destroy it in a short time, and that this would minimize civilian deaths and damage to infrastructure.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] It was expected that the elimination of the leadership would lead to the collapse of Iraq's military and government, and that much of the population would support the invaders once the government had been weakened.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Occupation of cities and attacks on peripheral military units were viewed as undesirable distractions.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Following Turkey's decision to deny any official use of its territory, the coalition was forced to modify the planned simultaneous attack from north and south.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Special Operations forces from the CIA and U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army managed to build and lead the Kurdish Peshmerga into an effective force and assault for the North.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The primary bases for the invasion were in Kuwait and other Persian Gulf states.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] One result of this was that one of the divisions intended for the invasion was forced to relocate and was unable to take part in the invasion until well into the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqis immediately adapted to the invasion, and began using unconventional tactics.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 22 March, American troops first encountered the insurgency tactics that would later define the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 1st Class Anthony Broadhead, a platoon sergeant in the Crazy Horse troop of the 3rd Infantry Division's cavalry unit, was in a tank heading towards a bridge in Samawah on the invasion route.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] He waved at a group of Iraqis, but instead of waving back, they began attacking the American tanks with AK-47 rifles, rocket-propelled grenades, and mortars.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Because these types of paramilitary forces were well-armed, but indistinguishable from civilians, they would come to pose a significant challenge for U.S. forces throughout Iraq War.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The invasion itself was swift, leading to the collapse of the Iraqi government and the military of Iraq in about three weeks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The oil infrastructure of Iraq was rapidly seized and secured with limited damage in that time.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Securing the oil infrastructure was considered of great importance.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Before the invasion, Iraqi forces had mined some 400 oil wells around Basra and the Al-Faw peninsula with explosives.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Coalition troops launched an air and amphibious assault on the Al-Faw peninsula during the closing hours of 19 March to secure the oil fields there; the amphibious assault was supported by warships of the Royal Navy, Polish Navy, and Royal Australian Navy.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 1 April, an F-14 from USS *Kitty Hawk* crashed in southern Iraq reportedly due to engine failure, and a S-3B Viking plunged off the deck of the USS *Constellation* after a malfunction and an AV-8B Harrier jump jet went into the Gulf while it was trying to land on the USS *Nassau*.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The British 3 Commando Brigade, with the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Navy's Special Boat Team 22, Task Unit Two, as well as the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Marine Corps' 15th Marine Expeditionary Unit and the Polish Special Forces unit GROM attached, attacked the port of Umm Qasr.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] There they met with heavy resistance by Iraqi troops.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A total of 14 coalition troops and 30–40 Iraqi troops were killed, and 450 Iraqis taken prisoner.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The British Army's 16 Air Assault Brigade alongside elements of the RAF Regiment also secured the oil fields in southern Iraq in places like Rumaila while the Polish commandos captured offshore oil platforms near the port, preventing their destruction.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Despite the rapid advance of the invasion forces, some 44 oil wells were destroyed and set ablaze by Iraqi explosives or by incidental fire.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However, the wells were quickly capped and the fires put out, preventing the ecological damage and loss of oil production capacity that had occurred at the end of the Gulf War.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In keeping with the rapid advance plan, the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 3rd Infantry Division moved westward and then northward through the western desert toward Baghdad, while the 1st Marine Expeditionary Force moved along Highway 1 through the center of the country, and 1 (UK) Armoured Division moved northward through the eastern marshland.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] During the first week of the war, Iraqi forces fired a Scud missile at the American Battlefield Update Assessment center in Camp Doha, Kuwait.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The missile was intercepted and shot down by a Patriot missile seconds before hitting the complex.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Subsequently, two A-10 Warthogs attacked the missile launcher.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Initially, the U.S.' 1st Marine Division fought through the Rumaila oil fields, and moved north to Nasiriyah—a moderate-sized, Shi'ite-dominated city with important strategic significance as a major road junction and its proximity to nearby Tallil Airfield.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] It was also situated near a number of strategically important bridges over the Euphrates River.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The city was defended by a mix of regular Iraqi army units, Ba'ath loyalists, and Fedayeen from both Iraq and abroad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army 3rd Infantry Division defeated Iraqi forces entrenched in and around the airfield and bypassed the city to the west.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 23 March, a convoy from the 3rd Infantry Division, including the female American soldiers Jessica Lynch, Shoshana Johnson, and Lori Piestewa, was ambushed after taking a wrong turn into the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eleven U.S. soldiers were killed, and seven, including Lynch and Johnson, were captured.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Piestewa died of wounds shortly after capture, while the remaining five prisoners of war were later rescued.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Piestewa, who was from Tuba City, Arizona, and an enrolled member of the Hopi Tribe, was believed to have been the first Native American woman killed in combat in a foreign war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Marines from the 2nd Marine Division entered Nasiriyah in force, facing heavy resistance as they moved to secure two major bridges in the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Several marines were killed during a firefight with Fedayeen in the urban fighting.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At the Saddam Canal, another 18 marines were killed in heavy fighting with Iraqi soldiers.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] An Air Force A-10 was involved in a case of friendly fire that resulted in the death of six Marines when it accidentally attacked an American amphibious vehicle.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Two other vehicles were destroyed when a barrage of RPG and small arms fire killed most of the Marines inside.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A Marine from Marine Air Control Group 28 was killed by enemy fire, and two Marine engineers drowned in the Saddam Canal.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The bridges were secured and the Second Marine division set up a perimeter around the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On the evening of 24 March, the 2nd Light Armored Reconnaissance Battalion, which was attached to Regimental Combat Team One (RCT-1), pushed through Nasiriyah and established a perimeter 15 km (9.3 miles) north of the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Iraqi reinforcements from Kut launched several counterattacks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Marines managed to repel them using indirect fire and close air support.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The last Iraqi attack was beaten off at dawn.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The battalion estimated that 200–300 Iraqi soldiers were killed, without a single U.S. casualty.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Nasiriyah was declared secure, but attacks by Iraqi Fedayeen continued.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] These attacks were uncoordinated, and resulted in firefights that killed many Fedayeen.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Because of Nasiriyah's strategic position as a road junction, significant gridlock occurred as U.S. forces moving north converged on the city's surrounding highways.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] With the Nasiriyah and Tallil Airfields secured, coalition forces gained an important logistical center in southern Iraq and established FOB/EAF Jalibah, some 10 miles (16 km) outside Nasiriyah.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Additional troops and supplies were soon brought through this forward operating base.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 101st Airborne Division continued its attack north in support of the 3rd Infantry Division.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] By 28 March, a severe sandstorm slowed the coalition advance as the 3rd Infantry Division halted its northward drive halfway between Najaf and Karbala.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Air operations by helicopters, poised to bring reinforcements from the 101st Airborne, were blocked for three days.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] There was particularly heavy fighting in and around the bridge near the town of Kufl.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Another fierce battle was at Najaf, where U.S. airborne and armored units with British air support fought an intense battle with Iraqi Regulars, Republican Guard units, and paramilitary forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] AH-64 Apache helicopter gunships setting out on a mission to attack Republican Guard armored units; while flying low the Apaches came under heavy anti-aircraft, small arms, and RPG fire which heavily damaged many helicopters and shot one down, frustrating the attack.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] They attacked again successfully on 26 March, this time after a pre-mission artillery barrage and with support from F/A-18 Hornet jets, with no gunships lost.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 1st Brigade Combat Team's air defense battery supported by a COLT (combat observation lasing team) and the Brigade Recon Troop moved in to secure the bridge at Al Kifl late on 24 March.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] When the ADA company was unable to secure the western bank of the bridge the commander called for reinforcements.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Grimsley order LTC Marcone Task Force 3-69 Armor to send a quick reaction force to support the ADA company.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] LTC Marcone sent B 3-7 Infantry to clear and secure the bridge.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Bravo Company was made up of two infantry platoons with M2A2 Bradley Fighting Vehicles and one platoon of M1A2 Abrams tanks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Bravo 3-7 Infantry secured the bridge and fought for 36 hours through a sandstorm.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] During that time, the soldiers fought against Iraqi Military and Fedayeen forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] After 36 hours, B co 3-7 Infantry was relieved on 26 March.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The 101st Airborne Division on 29 March, supported by a battalion from the 1st Armored Division, attacked Iraqi forces in the southern part of the city, near the Imam Ali Mosque and captured Najaf's airfield.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Four Americans were killed by a suicide bomber.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 31 March, the 101st made a reconnaissance-in-force into Najaf.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 1 April, elements of the 70th Armored Regiment launched a "Thunder Run", an armored thrust through Najaf's city center, and, with air support, defeated the Iraqi forces after several days of heavy fighting.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqi port city of Umm Qasr was the first British obstacle.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A joint Polish-British-American force ran into unexpectedly stiff resistance, and it took several days to clear the Iraqi forces out.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Farther north, the British 7 Armoured Brigade, fought their way into Iraq's second-largest city, Basra, on 6 April, coming under constant attack by regulars and Fedayeen, while 3rd Battalion, The Parachute Regiment cleared the 'old quarter' of the city that was inaccessible to vehicles.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Entering Basra was achieved after two weeks of fierce fighting, including a tank battle when the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards destroyed 14 Iraqi tanks on 27 March.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A few members of D Squadron, British SAS, were deployed to southern Iraq to support the coalition advance on Basra.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The team conducted forward route reconnaissance and infiltrated the city and brought in strikes on the Ba'athist loyalist leadership.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Elements of 1 (UK) Armoured Division began to advance north towards U.S. positions around Al Amarah on 9 April.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Pre-existing electrical and water shortages continued throughout the conflict and looting began as Iraqi forces collapsed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] After a rapid initial advance, the first major pause occurred near Karbala.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army elements met resistance from Iraqi troops defending cities and key bridges along the Euphrates River.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] These forces threatened to interdict supply routes as American forces moved north.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eventually, troops from the 101st Airborne Division of the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Army secured the cities of Najaf and Karbala to prevent any Iraqi counterattacks on the 3rd Infantry Division's lines of communication as the division pressed its advance toward Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Eleven British soldiers were killed, while 395–515 Iraqi soldiers, irregulars, and Fedayeen were killed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The efforts of the British Army facilitated the re-establishment of the rail lines from the port to Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Karbala Gap was a 20–25-mile wide strip of land with the Euphrates River to the east and Lake Razazah to the west.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] This strip of land was recognized by Iraqi commanders as a key approach to Baghdad, and was defended by some of the best units of the Iraqi Republican Guard.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Iraqi high command had originally positioned two Republican Guard divisions blocking the Karbala Gap.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Here these forces suffered heavy coalition air attacks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However, the coalition had since the beginning of March been conducting a strategic deception operation to convince the Iraqis that the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] 4th Infantry Division would be mounting a major assault into northern Iraq from Turkey.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] As part of Task Force 20, their formal role was to conduct selected high-priority site exploitation on suspected chemical weapon facilities before heading for the Haditha Dam complex.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Along the way, Delta supported the seizure of H-3 Air Base and also conducted numerous deception operations to confuse the Iraqis as to the disposition of coalition forces in the west.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] On 18 March 2003, B and D Squadrons of the British 22nd SAS Regiment had now infiltrated Iraq in full strength (D Squadron by air and B Squadron by ground) along with 1 Squadron Australian SASR and headed for H-2 and H-3 Air Base.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] They set up observation posts and called in airstrikes that defeated the Iraqi defenders.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The combined British and Australian Squadrons took H-2 virtually unopposed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] H-3 was secured on 25 March with the assistance of members of Delta Force and by Green Beret ODAs from Bravo company, 1st Battalion 5th SFG; a company of Rangers and Royal Marines from 45 Commando flew from Jordan to the bases and the base was handed over to them.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The SAS teams moved to the next objective – the intersection of the two main highways linking Baghdad with Syria and Jordan, where both squadrons were involved in conducting interdictions of fleeing Iraqi leadership targets heading for Syria.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] In northern Iraq in early March, a small reconnaissance team from M Squadron of the British Special Boat Service mounted on Honda ATVs inserted into Iraq from Jordan.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Its first mission was to conduct reconnaissance of an Iraqi air base at al-Sahara.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The team was compromised by an anti-special forces Fedayeen unit and barely escaped thanks to a U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] F-15E that flew air cover for the team and an RAF Chinook that extracted the team from out under the Fedayeen's "noses".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] However the Squadron was compromised by a goat herder; the SBS drove for several days while unknown to them anti-special forces Fedayeen units followed them.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] At an overnight position near Mosul, the Fedayeen ambushed the Squadron with DShK heavy machine guns and RPGs, the SBS returned fire and began taking fire from a T-72, the Squadron scattered and escaped the well-constructed trap.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] A number of Land Rovers became bogged down in a nearby wadi, so they mined the vehicles and abandoned them – though several did not detonate and were captured and exhibited on Iraqi television.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The SBS was now in three distinct groups: one with several operational Land Rovers was being pursued by the Iraqi hunter force, a second mainly equipped with ATVs was hunkered down and trying to arrange extraction, the third with just 2 operators on an ATV raced for the Syrian border.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The second group was also extracted by an RAF Chinook and the third group made it to Syria and was held there until their release was negotiated, there were no SBS casualties.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] Viking Hammer was set to begin on 21 March, however, the ground component of the operation was set back several days owing to the issues around infiltrating most of the 3rd Battalion 10th SFG into Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p02] The Islamic Group of Kurdistan surrendered after having suffered 100 men killed in the 21 March strikes.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 28 March, the ground element of Operation Viking Hammer was finally launched with a six-pronged advance, each prong was composed of several ODAs from 3rd Battalion, 10th SFG and upwards of 1,000 Kurdish Peshmerga fighters.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main advance set off towards Sargat – the location of the suspected chemical and biological weapons site; the force was soon pinned down by DShK heavy machine-gun fire from the surrounding hills.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy F/A-18s responded to an urgent CAS request from the force and dropped two 500lb JDAMs on the Ansar al-Islam machine gun nests and strafed the positions with 20 mm cannon before departing due to being low on fuel.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The advance began again only to be halted once more by fire from prepared DShK and PKM machine gun nests, Green Berets from ODA 081 deployed a Mk 19 grenade launcher from the back of a Toyota Tacoma and suppressed the gun positions allowing the Peshmerga to assault and wipe out the terrorists.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After capturing the town of Gulp, the force continued onto the village of Sargat; the village was heavily defended by fortified fighting positions mounting DShKs and mortars along with several BM-21 Grad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Unable to call in airstrikes due to the close proximity of the Peshmerga, a Green Beret sergeant used a dismounted M2 HMG to suppress the entrenched terrorists, his actions allowed the Peshmerga to bring forward their own 82 mm Mortars and Grads which forced the Ansar al-Islam fighters to retreat.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] To dislodge the terrorists, the Combat Controllers attached to the ODAs vectored in U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy F/A-18s which dropped six 500 lb JDAMs that shut down any further resistance.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] With their objectives completed, the 3rd Battalion and their Peshmerga returned to the green line to assist the push on Kirkuk and Mosul.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A specialist SSE team was brought in to document the find at Sargat, the team recovered traces of several chemicals including Ricin along with stocks of NBC protective suits, atropine injectors and Arabic manuals on chemical weapons and IED construction.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates of Ansar al-Islam dead number over 300, many of them foreign fighters, while only 22 Peshmerga fighters were killed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Turkey had officially prohibited any coalition troops from using their bases or airspace, so lead elements of the 10th SFG had to make a detour infiltration; their flight was supposed to take four hours but instead took ten.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 22 March, the majority of 2nd and 3rd Battalions 10th SFG, from Task Force Viking flew from their forward staging area in Constanta, Romania to a location near Irbil aboard six MC-130H Combat Talons.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Several were engaged by Iraqi air defences on the flight into northern Iraq (one was sufficiently damaged enough that it was forced to make an emergency landing at Incirlik Air Base).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The initial lift had deployed 19 Green Beret ODAs and four ODBs into northern Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Hours after the first of such flights, Turkey did allow the use of its air space and the rest of the 10th SFG infiltrated in.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The preliminary mission was to destroy the base of the Kurdish terrorist group Ansar al-Islam, believed to be linked to al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Concurrent and follow-on missions involved attacking and fixing Iraqi forces in the north, thus preventing their deployment to the southern front and the main effort of the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Eventually Task Force Viking would number 51 ODAs and ODBs alongside some 60,000 Kurdish Peshmerga militia of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 26 March, the 173rd Airborne Brigade augmented the invasion's northern front by parachuting into northern Iraq onto Bashur Airfield, controlled at the time by elements of 10th SFG and Kurdish peshmerga.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The fall of Kirkuk on 10 April to the 10th SFG, CIA Paramilitary Teams and Kurdish peshmerga precipitated the 173rd's planned assault, preventing the unit's involvement in combat against Iraqi forces during the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Following the Battle of Haditha Dam, Delta Force handed the dam over to the Rangers and headed north to conduct ambushes along the highway above Tikrit, tying up Iraqi forces in the region and attempting to capture fleeing high-value targets trying to escape to Syria.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 2 April, Delta was engaged by half a dozen armed technicals from the same anti-special forces Fedayeen that had previously fought the SBS.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Two Delta operators were wounded (one serious); the squadron requested an urgent aeromedical evacuation and immediate close-air support as a company of truck-borne Iraqi reinforcements arrived.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The DAPs spotted several Iraqi units and engaged them until they were dangerously low on fuel.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Task Force Viking launched an operation to seize the town of Ain Sifni.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The town was strategically important because it straddles the main highway into Mosul.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Once the town fell, it would be clear for the coalition to advance on Mosul.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs from the 3rd and 10th SFG called in airstrikes on the Iraqi garrisons in and around the town, causing many of the Iraqi conscripts to flee.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] By 5 April 2003, there appeared to be only two Iraqi platoons left in the town.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 6 April, ODAs 051, 055, and 056 assaulted the town – ODAs 055 and 056 provided fire support along with Peshmerga heavy weapons teams, while ODA 51 made the actual assault on the town.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] As ODA 51 cautiously advanced on the village, it came under intense fire – the two platoons of Iraqis turned out to be closer to battalion strength and equipped with heavy weapons like 82 mm mortars, anti-aircraft guns, and an artillery piece.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After four hours of F/A-18 airstrikes and constant heavy weapons fire from ODA 055 and 056, the assault force entered Ain Sifni; soon afterward, Iraqi infantry counterattacked, supported by several mortars, attempting to retake the town, but it was beaten back by ODA 51 and the Kurds.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 6 April, ODA 391 and ODA 392 from the 3rd SFG and ODA 044 from 10th SFG with about 150 Kurdish fighters were the main force involved in the Battle of Debecka Pass.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April, nine ODAs from FOB 103 encircled Kirkuk after fierce fighting to capture the ridges overlooking the approaches to the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The earlier capture of the nearby city of Tuz had largely broken the will of the Iraqi Army and only the Fedayeen remained in Kirkuk.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The first ODA units entered the city the next day; a week later the 173rd Airborne took over responsibility for the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After some minor skirmishes the Fedayeen fled.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Staging out of MSS Grizzly, Delta mounted operations to interdict Ba'ath Party HVTs on Highway 1 (Highway 2 and 4 in western Iraq had been secured by British SAS and Australian SAS teams), on 9 April, the combined team seized an airfield near Tikrit.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 173rd Brigade would eventually take responsibility for Kirkuk days later, becoming involved in the counterinsurgency fight and remain there until redeploying a year later.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 11 April, an advanced element from FOB 102, numbering no more than thirty Green Berets, advanced into Mosul.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The advance had followed several days of heavy airstrikes on three Iraqi divisions defending Mosul.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 13 April, 3rd Battalion 3rd SFG and a battalion from the 10th Mountain Division were ordered to Mosul to relieve the 10th SFG and their Peshmerga allies.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Further reinforcing operations in northern Iraq, the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit (Special Operations Capable), serving as Landing Force Sixth Fleet, deployed in April to Erbil and subsequently Mosul via Marine KC-130 flights.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 26 MEU (SOC) maintained security of the Mosul airfield and surrounding area until relief by the 101st Airborne Division.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 21 March, ODA 554 of Bravo Company, 2nd Battalion 5th SFG crossed the border with the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They later rejoined the other half of the team and fought roving bands of Fedayeen.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The ODAs next mission was to work with a CIA-recruited Sheikh and assist British forces in identifying targets around Basra.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The ODA soon established an informant network, they eventually assisted the British in rounding up some 170 Fedayeen in the city; they were eventually replaced by members of G Squadron 22nd SAS Regiment.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Battle of Haditha Dam occurred on 24 March 2003, Rangers from 3rd Battalion, 75th Ranger Regiment, conducted a combat parachute drop onto H-1 Air Base, securing the site as a staging area for operations in the west.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Delta Force recce operators drove through Iraqi lines around the Haditha Dam on customised ATVs, marking targets for coalition airstrikes resulting in the eventual destruction of a large number of Iraqi armoured vehicles and anti aircraft systems.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Delta's reconnaissance of the dam indicated that a larger force would be needed to seize it, so a request was made and approved for a second Delta squadron from Fort Bragg to be dispatched with a further Ranger battalion, along with M1A1 Abrams tanks from C Company, 2nd Battalion 70th Armor.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] C-17 flew the company from Tallil to H-1 and then to MSS (Mission Support Site) Grizzly – a desert strip established by Delta Force located between Haditha and Tikrit; C Squadron, Delta Force was flown directly to MSS Grizzly.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 1 April, C squadron, Delta Force and 3/75th Ranger Regiment conducted a night-time ground assault in their Pinzgauers and GMVs against the Haditha Dam complex.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three platoons of Rangers seized the dams' administrative buildings with little initial opposition, while a pair of AH-6M Six Guns orbited overhead.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After daybreak, a Ranger sniper shot and killed 3 Iraqis carrying RPGs on the western side of the dam and Rangers on the eastern side engaged a truck carrying infantry, which led to an hour-long contract.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] South of the dam, another Ranger platoon was securing the dam's power station and electricity transformer against sabotage, another platoon was occupied establishing blocking positions on the main road into the dam complex.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The blocking positions came under the sporadic mortar fire, resulting in the AH-6Ms flying multiple gun runs to silence the mortar positions, another mortar team, firing from a small island was engaged and silenced by a Ranger Javelin team.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Rangers captured an Iraqi forward observer dressed as a civilian after sinking his kayak with .50cal fire, the observer had maps of the Rangers positions.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A-10As engaged nearby electricity transformers successfully blacking out the area, but it resulted in a series of explosions and a resulting fire at the stations that dramatically lit the sky – pinpointing the orbiting helicopters for enemy gunmen.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The SEALs conducted a hasty SSE while the Ranger blocking positions received and returned fire, the AH-6Ms and the aerial snipers continued to engage enemy gunmen while the DAPs pushed further out to ensure no reinforcements approached – engaging and destroying numerous Fedayeen armed technicals.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The SSE took longer than expected owing to the size and maze-like structure of the building, the mission completed after 45 minutes, later tests of the material recovered by DEVGRU showed no evidence of chemical or biological weapons at the Objective Beaver.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo and Charlie companies of 1st Battalion 5th SFG crossed the Kuwait border at H-Hour with ODA 531 using breaching demolition charges to clear a path through the sand berms.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Charlie company's seven ODAs in 35 vehicles took the southeastern operation box of the western desert heading towards the towns of Nukyab, Habbariya and Mudyasis, ODA's 534 and 532 split off to head for the area surrounding Nukyab searching for mobile Scud-B TEL launch sites.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 532 also inserted a mobile weather station that provided planners with vital real time weather updates of the battle space.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo company set out for the central town of Ar Rutba and H-3 Air Base with six ODAs and a support ODB (Operational Detachment Bravo).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs 523 and 524 searched a suspected Scud-B storage facility while ODAs 521 and 525 were tasked with clearing several abandoned airfields, with no sign of Scud launchers, ODA 525 deployed a Special Reconnaissance team to conduct pattern of life surveillance on the town of Ar Rutba.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A two-man team called in a pair of nearby F-16C Fighting Falcons to destroy an Iraqi Army radio direction-finding facility they had identified.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 525 attempted to link up with the two-man reconnaissance team and extract it to safety but large numbers of Iraqi vehicles began driving out of the town to them, the ODAs called in immediate air support.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While waiting, the reconnaissance team and Target Acquisition Marines fired on the Fedayeen leaders with their suppressed MK12 sniper rifle and contacted ODA 521 (who were clearing suspects east of the town) and they reinforced ODA 525.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Over 100 Fedayeen fighters were killed and four armed technicals were destroyed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] To the west ODA 523 reinforced ODA 524, but ran into a pair of armed technicals on the highway, both were destroyed by the GMVs, the Green Berets ceased fire when a civilian station wagon full of Iraqi children drove into the middle of the firefight.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 522 also identified two Fedayeen armed technicals proceeding down the highway toward ODA 523, they set an ambush for them, destroying the vehicles and killing 15 Fedayeen.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The strategic intent of the US Army Special Forces ODAs had been to shut down the main supply routes and deny access around Ar Rutbah and the strategically important H-3 air base, which was defended by a battalion of Iraqi troops and significant numbers of mobile and static anti aircraft guns.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 521 over watching the highway they were travelling on ambushed the convoy destroying a truck mounted ZU-23, the convoy was thrown into disarray, a sandstorm prevented the ODA calling in airstrikes and the convoy scattered into the desert.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Bravo company 5th SFG and the coalition SOF secured the airfield, finding a Roland surface-to-air missile system, around 80 assorted anti aircraft cannon guns including ZSU-23-4 Shilka, SA-7 grail handheld SAMs and an enormous amount of ammunition.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Additionally, ODA 523 discovered what may have been chemical weapons samples in a laboratory on the grounds of H-3.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODAs guided precision airstrikes on Fedayeen anti aircraft guns on the outskirts of the town and on top of the airstrikes, they also struck large groups of Fedayeen militia with Javelin missiles.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April, nine ODAs secured the main roads into the town and commenced a day of near continuous final airstrikes from fix-wing aircraft and Apache helicopters.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Civilians from the town approached the Green Berets asking them to stop the bombing, the Green Berets struck a deal with the civilians and they entered the town the next day.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A B-52 and 2 F-16Cs flew show of force flights over the town as the Green Berets entered, the Fedayeen blended in with the population.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Within days, the Green Berets helped the town to elect a mayor and set up markets, get sixty percent of the electricity grid working and repair water supplies.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 521 and 525 continued to operate in the region, stopping several trucks carrying foreign fighters, they disarmed them, took their details and warned them not to come back before sending them to Syria; in late May, the teams were replaced by the 3rd Armoured Cavalry Regiment.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army Special Forces (Green Berets) conducted reconnaissance in the cities of Basra, Karbala and various other locations.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After Sargat was taken, Bravo Company, 3rd Battalion, 10th SFG and CIA paramilitary officers along with their Kurdish allies pushed south towards Tikrit and the surrounding towns of Northern Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Previously, during the Battle of the Green Line, Bravo Company, 3/10 with their Kurdish allies pushed back, destroyed, or routed the 13th Iraqi Infantry Division.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraq was the largest deployment of the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] ODA 563 worked in support of the US Marines around Al Diwaniyah with local Sheikhs and their militias supported by AV-8Bs and F/A-18s; managing to capture the city of Qwam al Hamza.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The following day ODA 563, their local Sheikh and his militia and a small Force Recon team captured the bridge leading to Diwaniyah and the militia attacked Iraqi positions over the bridge, forcing the Iraqi army and Fedayeen to flee toward Baghdad while being harassed by Marine Corps aircraft.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Private first class Jessica Lynch of the 507th Maintenance Company was seriously injured and captured after her convoy was ambushed by Iraqi forces during the Battle of Nasiriyah.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Initial intelligence that led to her rescue was provided by an informant who approached ODA 553 when it was working in Nasiriyah, the intelligence was passed on and Task Force 20 planned a rescue mission.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The plan called for Task Force Tarawa to conduct a deception mission by seizing the bridges across the Euphrates to draw attention away from the hospital Lynch was held at, an airstrike by U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine AV-8 Harriers would be conducted against one of the bridges to confuse the opposition further and U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine AH-1W Cobras were tasked to fly over the area to conceal the sound of incoming SOF helicopters.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Air cover was provided by an AC-130 Spectre and a Marine EA-6B Prowler to jam any enemy SAM systems that might be present.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main assault force of SEALs would arrive by a ground convoy of AGMS Pandur forearmed vehicles and GMV trucks while the hostage rescue element landed directly on the objective in MH-6 Little Birds.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] At 0100 on 1 April 2003, TF Tarawa commenced their deception mission, CIA elements cut the city's power as the helicopters approached their objective, the AH-6s led the way, behind them the MH-6s dropped off Task Force 20 sniper teams at strategic locations around and on the hospital.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The DAPs and the AH-6s covered the MH-60Ks as they dropped off assault teams on the hospital roof and another by the front door, the ground assault convoy arrived and the assaulters raced inside and onto the second floor where Lynch was located.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] 13 minutes later, a MH-60K touched down near the hospital entrance with a team of PJs and SOAR medics on board and transported Lynch to Tallil where it rendezvoused with a standby medical flight and then onto Kuwait, and finally the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Task Force 20 carried out one of the first successful U.S. prisoner of war rescue missions since World War II.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three weeks into the invasion, the Army's 3rd Infantry Division, with the 1st Marine Division also present, moved into Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Units of the Iraqi Special Republican Guard led the defence of the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The rest of the defenders were a mixture of Republican Guard units, regular army units, Fedayeen Saddam, and non-Iraqi Arab volunteers.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Initial plans were for coalition units to surround the city and gradually move in, forcing Iraqi armor and ground units to cluster into a central pocket in the city, and then attack with air and artillery forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This plan soon became unnecessary, as an initial engagement of armored units south of the city saw most of the Republican Guard's assets destroyed and routes in the southern outskirts of the city occupied.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 5 April, Task Force 1–64 Armor of the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army's 3rd Infantry Division executed a raid, later called the "Thunder Run", to test remaining Iraqi defenses, with 29 tanks and 14 Bradley armored fighting vehicles advancing to the Baghdad airport.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They met significant resistance, but were successful in reaching the airport, and eventually secured it after heavy fighting.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The next day, another brigade of the 3rd Infantry Division attacked downtown Baghdad and occupied one of the palaces of Saddam Hussein in fierce fighting.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marines also faced heavy shelling from Iraqi artillery as they attempted to cross a river bridge, but the river crossing was successful.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqis managed to inflict some casualties on the U.S. forces near the airport from defensive positions but suffered severe casualties from air bombardment.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Within hours of the palace seizure and with television coverage of this spreading through Iraq, U.S. forces ordered Iraqi forces within Baghdad to surrender, or the city would face a full-scale assault.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraqi government officials had either disappeared or had conceded defeat.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 9 April 2003, Baghdad was formally occupied by coalition forces, and a statue of Saddam was toppled.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Much of Baghdad remained unsecured, however, and fighting continued within the city and its outskirts well into the period of occupation.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Saddam had vanished, and his whereabouts were unknown.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 10 April, a rumor emerged that Saddam Hussein and his top aides were in a mosque complex in the Al Az'Amiyah District of Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Three companies of Marines were sent to capture him and came under heavy fire from rocket-propelled grenades, mortars, and assault rifles.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One Marine was killed and 20 were wounded, but neither Saddam or any of his top aides were found.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. forces supported by mortars, artillery, and aircraft continued to attack Iraqi forces still loyal to Saddam Hussein and non-Iraqi Arab volunteers.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. aircraft flying in support were met with Iraqi anti-aircraft fire.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 12 April, by late afternoon, all fighting had ceased.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A total of 34 American soldiers and 2,320 Iraqi fighters were killed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many Iraqis celebrated the downfall of Saddam by vandalizing the many portraits and statues of him together with other pieces of his cult of personality.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One widely publicized event was the dramatic toppling of a large statue of Saddam in Baghdad's Firdos Square.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This attracted considerable media coverage at the time.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The fall of Baghdad saw the outbreak of regional, sectarian violence throughout the country, as Iraqi tribes and cities began to fight each other over old grudges.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi cities of Al-Kut and Nasiriyah launched attacks on each other immediately following the fall of Baghdad to establish dominance in the new country, and the U.S.-led coalition quickly found themselves embroiled in a potential civil war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S.-led coalition forces ordered the cities to cease hostilities immediately, explaining that Baghdad would remain the capital of the new Iraqi government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Nasiriyah responded favorably and quickly backed down; however, Al-Kut placed snipers on the main roadways into town, with orders that invading forces were not to enter the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After several minor skirmishes, the snipers were removed, but tensions and violence between regional, city, tribal, and familial groups continued.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Tommy Franks assumed control of Iraq as the supreme commander of the coalition occupation forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Shortly after the sudden collapse of the defense of Baghdad, rumors were circulating in Iraq and elsewhere that there had been a deal struck (a "safqua") wherein the U.S.-led coalition had bribed key members of the Iraqi military elite and/or the Ba'ath party itself to stand down.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In May 2003, Franks retired, and confirmed in an interview that the U.S.-led coalition had paid Iraqi military leaders to defect.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The extent of the defections and their effect on the war are unclear.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S.-led coalition troops promptly began searching for the key members of Saddam's government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] These individuals were identified by a variety of means, most famously through sets of most-wanted Iraqi playing cards.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Later during the military occupation period after the invasion, on 22 July during a raid by the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] 101st Airborne Division and men from Task Force 20, Uday and Qusay Hussein, as well as one of Saddam's grandsons were killed in a massive fire-fight.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Saddam himself was captured on 13 December.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] U.S. special forces had also been involved in the extreme south of Iraq, attempting to occupy key roads to Syria and air bases.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In one case two armored platoons were used to convince Iraqi leadership that an entire armored battalion was entrenched in the west of Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 15 April, U.S. forces took control of Tikrit, the last major outpost in central Iraq, with an attack led by the Marines' Task Force Tripoli.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] About a week later, the Marines were relieved in place by the Army's 4th Infantry Division.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Coalition aircraft flew over 41,000 sorties, of which over 9,000 were tanker sorties.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the invasion, several factors contributed to the destabilization of Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Paul Bremer issued Coalition Provisional Authority Order Number 2, dissolving the Iraqi Army and other entities of the Ba'athist state.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Ba'athists were excluded from the newly formed Iraqi government.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The first postwar election was won by the United Iraqi Alliance, an electoral coalition composed of mainly Shi’ite groups, which proceeded to ostracize Sunnis.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Shia militia groups pushed Sunnis out of several areas, even emptying entire Sunni neighborhoods in Baghdad during the 2007 troop surge.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The U.S. military established prison camps where disgruntled Iraqis, former Ba'athists, and jihadists met.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, future leader of the Islamic State, joined al-Qaeda in Iraq (AQI) while detained at Camp Bucca in 2004.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] AQI member Ahmed al-Sharaa, the future leader of al-Nusra Front and Hay'at Tahrir al-Sham, and future Syrian president, was also held there and released in 2008.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] All these factors contributed to Iraq's sectarian violence and the formation and spread of terrorist organizations.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 1 May 2003, Bush gave a speech on the aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln*, announcing the end of major combat operations in the Iraq war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While he gave the speech, there was a banner hanging behind him that wrote "Mission Accomplished".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The banner, made by White House staff at the request of the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The White House subsequently released a statement that the sign and Bush's visit referred to the initial invasion of Iraq, and disputing the charge of theatrics.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The speech itself noted: "We have difficult work to do in Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] We are bringing order to parts of that country that remain dangerous." Post-invasion Iraq was marked by a long conflict between U.S.-led forces and Iraqi insurgents.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Australia contributed approximately 2,000 Australian Defence Force personnel, including a special forces task group, three warships and 14 F/A-18 Hornet aircraft.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 16 April 2003, Australian special operations forces captured the undefended Al Asad air base west of Baghdad.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The base would later become the second largest coalition facility post-invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Battle of Umm Qasr was the first military confrontation in the Iraq War, with its objective the capture of the port.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Polish GROM troops supported the amphibious assault on Umm Qasr with the British 3 Commando Brigade of the Royal Marines, and the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the waterway was de-mined by a Detachment from HM-14 and Naval Special Clearance Team ONE of the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Navy and reopened, Umm Qasr played an important role in the shipment of humanitarian supplies to Iraqi civilians.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In Operation TELIC, British troops participated in the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The 1st Armoured Division was deployed to the Persian Gulf and commanded British forces in the area, securing areas in southern Iraq, including the city of Basra during the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] A total of 46,000 troops of all the British services were committed to the operation at its start, including some 5,000 Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary sailors and 4,000 Royal Marines, 26,000 British Army soldiers, and 8,100 RAF airmen.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The British special forces deployment was codenamed Operation Row and were known as Task Force 7 under Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force-West (Task Force Dagger).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The U.S.-led coalition forces toppled the government and captured the key cities of a large nation in only 26 days.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The invasion did require a large army build-up like the 1991 Gulf War, but many did not see combat and many were withdrawn after the invasion ended.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This proved to be short-sighted, however, due to the requirement for a much larger force to combat the irregular Iraqi forces in the Iraqi insurgency.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Army Chief of Staff, recommended "several hundred thousand" troops be used to maintain post-war order, but then Rumsfeld—and especially his deputy, civilian Paul Wolfowitz—strongly disagreed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] General Abizaid later said General Shinseki had been right.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi army, armed mainly with older Soviet and Eastern European built equipment, was overall ill-equipped in comparison to the American and British forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Attacks on U.S. supply routes by Fedayeen militiamen were repulsed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqis' artillery proved largely ineffective, and they were unable to mobilize their air force to attempt a defense.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi T-72 tanks, the most powerful armored vehicles in the Iraqi army, were both outdated and ill-maintained, and when they were mobilized they were rapidly destroyed, thanks in part to the coalition air supremacy.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Air Force, Marine Corps and Naval Aviation, and RAF operated with impunity throughout the country, pinpointing heavily defended resistance targets and destroying them before ground troops arrived.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The main battle tanks of American and British forces, the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] M1 Abrams and British Challenger 2, functioned well in the rapid advance across the country.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Despite the many RPG attacks by irregular Iraqi forces, few U.S. and UK tanks were lost, and no tank crew-members were killed by hostile fire, although nearly 40 M1 Abrams were damaged in the attacks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The only tank loss sustained by the British Army was a Challenger 2 of the Queen's Royal Lancers that was hit by another Challenger 2, killing two crew members.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Iraqi army suffered from poor morale, even among the elite Republican Guard.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Entire units disbanded into the crowds upon the approach of invading troops, or actually sought out American and British forces to surrender to.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many Iraqi commanding officers were bribed by the CIA or coerced into surrendering.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The invasion force did not see the entire Iraqi military thrown against it; American and British units had orders to move to and seize objective target points rather than seek to engage Iraqi units.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This resulted in most regular Iraqi military units emerging from the war without having been engaged, and fully intact, especially in southern Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] It is assumed that most units disintegrated to return to their homes.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates on the number of casualties during the invasion in Iraq vary widely.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Estimates on civilian casualties are more variable than those for military personnel.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Approximately 7,500 civilians were killed during the invasion phase.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The Project on Defense Alternatives study estimated that 3,200–4,300 civilians died during the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Fedayeen Saddam militia, Republican Guard, and Iraqi security forces were reported to have executed Iraqi soldiers who tried to surrender on multiple occasions, as well as threatening the families of those who refused to fight.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] One such incident was directly observed during the Battle of Debecka Pass.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Many incidents of Fedayeen fighters using human shields were reported from various towns in Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Iraqi Republican Guard units were also reported to be using human shields.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Some reports indicate that the Fedayeen used ambulances to deliver messages and transport fighters into combat.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] On 31 March, Fedayeen in a Red Crescent-marked ambulance attacked American soldiers outside Nasiriyah, wounding three.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] During the Battle of Basra, British forces of the Black Watch reported that on 28 March, Fedayeen forces opened fire on thousands of civilian refugees fleeing the city.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After the ambush of the 507th Maintenance Company during the Battle of Nasiriyah on 23 March, the bodies of several Americans soldiers who had been killed in the ambush were shown on Iraqi television.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Some of these soldiers had visible gunshot wounds to the head, leading to speculation that they had been executed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Donald Walters, no evidence has since surfaced to support this scenario and it is generally accepted that the soldiers were killed in action.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Five live prisoners of war were also interviewed on the air, a violation of the Third Geneva Convention.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Sergeant Walters was initially reported to have been killed in the ambush after killing several Fedayeen before running out of ammunition.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] However, an eyewitness later reported that he had seen Walters being guarded by several Fedayeen in front of a building.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Forensics work later found Walters' blood in front of the building and blood spatter suggesting he died from two gunshot wounds to the back at close range.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] This led the Army to conclude that Walters had been executed after being captured, and he was posthumously awarded the Prisoner of War Medal in 2004.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] It was alleged in the authorized biography of Pfc.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Jessica Lynch that she was raped by her captors after her capture, based on medical reports and the pattern of her injuries, though this is not supported by Lynch.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Mohammed Odeh al-Rehaief, who later helped American forces rescue Lynch, stated that he saw an Iraqi Colonel slap Lynch while she was in her hospital bed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The staff at the hospital where Lynch was held later denied both stories, saying that Lynch was well cared for.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] While Lynch suffers from amnesia due to her injuries, she denied any mistreatment while in captivity.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Also on 23 March, a British Army engineering unit made a wrong turn near the town of Az Zubayr, which was still held by Iraqi forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The unit was ambushed and Sapper Luke Allsopp and Staff Sergeant Simon Cullingworth became separated from the rest.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Both were captured and executed by Iraqi irregular forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In 2006, a video of Allsopp lying on the ground surrounded by Iraqi irregular forces was discovered.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] During the Battle of Nasiriyah, Iraqi irregulars feigned surrender to approach an American unit securing a bridge.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] After getting close to the soldiers, the Iraqis suddenly opened fire, killing 10 soldiers and wounding 40.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In response, American forces reinforced security procedures for dealing with prisoners of war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] Marine Sergeant Fernando Padilla-Ramirez was reported missing from his supply unit after an ambush north of Nasiriyah on 28 March.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] His body was later dragged through the streets of Ash-Shatrah and hung in the town square, and later taken down and buried by sympathetic locals.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The corpse was discovered by U.S. forces on 10 April.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] In 2023, Amnesty International released a report calling for accountability and reparations for human rights violations perpetrated by the coalition during the invasion and subsequent occupation between 2003 and 2011.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] They cited violations of international humanitarian law including secret prisons, torture and other cruel treatment of detainees, indiscriminate attacks that killed and injured civilians, and forced disappearances.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The report stated that both Bush and Rumsfeld had publicly confessed to involvement in secret detentions and faced no criminal accountability.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p03] The report also noted that despite the conclusions of the International Criminal Court in 2020 that British forces had committed war crimes in Iraq, including deliberate killings, rape and torture, no senior British officials have been held criminally accountable.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Massive looting took place in the days following the 2003 invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] According to U.S. officials, the "reality of the situation on the ground" was that hospitals, water plants, and ministries with vital intelligence needed security more than other sites.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] There were only enough U.S. troops on the ground to guard a certain number of the many sites that ideally needed protection, and so, apparently, some "hard choices" were made.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It was reported that The Iraq Museum was among the looted sites.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The director at the time was archaeologist Nawala Al-Mutawalli.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The FBI was soon called into Iraq to track down the stolen items.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It was found that the initial allegations of looting of substantial portions of the collection were heavily exaggerated.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Initial reports asserted a near-total looting of the museum, estimated at upwards of 170,000 inventory lots, or about 501,000 pieces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The more recent estimate places the number of stolen pieces at around 15,000, and about 10,000 of them probably were taken in an "inside job" before U.S. troops arrived, according to Bogdanos.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Over 5,000 looted items have since been recovered.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] An assertion that U.S. forces did not guard the museum because they were guarding the Ministry of Oil and Ministry of Interior is disputed by investigator Colonel Matthew Bogdanos in his 2005 book *Thieves of Baghdad*.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bogdanos notes that the Ministry of Oil building was bombed, but the museum complex, which took some fire, was not bombed.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] He also writes that Saddam Hussein's troops set up sniper's nests inside and on top of the museum, and nevertheless U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Marines and soldiers stayed close enough to prevent wholesale looting.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] András Riedlmayer, a specialist in Islamic architecture at Harvard University, said the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] State Department had asked him for advice before the invasion, and that "everybody warned them that the greatest danger was not from Tomahawk missiles but from looting." Keith D.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] More serious for the post-war state of Iraq was the looting of cached weaponry and ordnance which fueled the subsequent insurgency.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] As many as 250,000 tons of explosives were unaccounted for by October 2004.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Defense Department led to delays in the post-invasion assessment and protection of Iraqi nuclear facilities.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Tuwaitha, the Iraqi site most scrutinized by UN inspectors since 1991, was left unguarded and was looted.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Ancient history professor Zainab Bahrani reported that a helicopter landing pad was constructed in the center of the ancient city of Babylon, and "removed layers of archeological earth from the site.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The daily flights of the helicopters rattle the ancient walls and the winds created by their rotors blast sand against the fragile bricks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] As of 2007, the invasion was the most widely and closely reported war in military history.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Television network coverage was largely pro-war and viewers were six times more likely to see a pro-war source as one who was anti-war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] *The New York Times* ran a number of articles describing Saddam Hussein's attempts to build weapons of mass destruction.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The 8 September 2002 article titled "U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Says Hussein Intensifies Quest for A-Bomb Parts" was later discredited, leading *The New York Times* to issue a public statement admitting it was not as rigorous as it should have been.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] At the start of the war, as many as 775 reporters and photographers were traveling as embedded journalists.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These reporters signed contracts with the military that limited what they were allowed to report on.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] When asked why the military decided to embed journalists with the troops, Lt.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Marine Corps replied, "Frankly, our job is to win the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2003, a study released by Fairness & Accuracy in Reporting stated the network news disproportionately focused on pro-war sources and left out many anti-war sources.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] According to the study, 64% of total sources supported the war, while total anti-war sources made up 10% of the media (only 3% of U.S. sources were anti-war).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The study looked only at six American news networks after 20 March for three weeks.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] A September 2003 poll revealed that 70% of Americans believed Saddam was involved in 9/11.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] 80% of Fox News viewers were found to hold at least one such belief about the invasion, compared to 23% of PBS viewers.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Ted Turner, founder of CNN, charged that Rupert Murdoch was using Fox News to advocate an invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Critics argued that this statistic is indicative of misleading coverage by the U.S. media, since viewers in other countries were less likely to have these beliefs.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Independent media also played a prominent role in covering the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Indymedia network, among many other independent networks including many journalists from the invading countries, provided reports on the Iraq war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In the U.S., the radio program *Democracy Now* was critical of the invasion, and crimes committed by the U.S. in Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Israeli Military Censor have released gag orders to Fresh and Rotter news platforms preventing them releasing any information about events and action related to the invasion.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Australian war artist George Gittoes collected independent interviews with soldiers while producing his documentary *Soundtrack To War*.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The Iraq War provided the first time in history that military on the front lines were able to provide direct, uncensored reportage themselves, thanks to blogging software and the reach of the internet.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Dozens of such reporting sites, known as soldier blogs or milblogs, were started during the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These blogs were more often than not largely pro-war and stated various reasons why the soldiers and Marines felt they were doing the right thing.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] International coverage of the war differed from coverage in the U.S. in a number of ways.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Arab-language news channel Al Jazeera and the German satellite channel Deutsche Welle featured almost twice as much information on the political background of the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Al Jazeera also showed scenes of civilian casualties and insurgent attacks rarely seen in the U.S. media.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The central U.S. justification for launching the war was that Saddam's alleged development of nuclear and biological weapons and purported ties to al-Qaeda made his regime a "grave and growing" threat to the U.S. and international community.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] During the lead-up to the war and the aftermath of the invasion, critics cast doubt on the evidence supporting this rationale.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] After the build-up of U.S. troops in neighboring states, Saddam welcomed them back and promised complete cooperation with their demands.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Experienced IAEA inspection teams were already back in Iraq and had made some interim reports on its search for various forms of WMD.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Wilson investigated the contention that Iraq had sought uranium for nuclear weapons in Niger and reported that the contention had no substance.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Similarly, alleged links between Iraq and al-Qaeda were called into question during the lead-up to the war, and were discredited by a 2004 report from U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Senator Carl Levin, which was later corroborated by a 2006 report from the Defense Department's inspector general.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] These reports further alleged that Bush administration officials, particularly former undersecretary of defense Douglas J.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Feith, manipulated evidence to support links between al-Qaeda and Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] An FBI agent who interrogated Saddam at this time stated in 2008 that while Iraq may not have possessed WMDs after the 1990s, Saddam likely intended to restart the WMD program if given the opportunity to do so.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] One of the main questions in the lead-up to the war was whether the UNSC would authorize military intervention in Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It became increasingly clear that this authorization would require significant further weapons inspections.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Many criticized their effort as unwise, immoral, and illegal.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Robin Cook, then-leader of the UK House of Commons and a former foreign secretary, resigned from Blair's cabinet in protest over the UK's decision to invade without UN authorization.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Cook said at the time that: "In principle, I believe it is wrong to embark on military action without broad international support.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In practice, I believe it is against Britain's interests to create a precedent for unilateral military action." In addition, senior government legal advisor Elizabeth Wilmshurst resigned, stating her legal opinion that an invasion would be illegal.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in September 2004, "[F]rom our point of view, and from the Charter point of view, [the war] was illegal." This drew immediate criticism from the U.S., and was immediately played down.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The most relevant to this issue is Resolution 678".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Criticisms about the evidence used to justify the war notwithstanding, many opponents of military intervention objected, saying that a diplomatic solution would be preferable, and that war should be reserved as a truly last resort.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] (...) Faithful to its values, it wishes resolutely to act with all the members of the international community.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] It believes in our ability to build together a better world." The direct opposition between diplomatic solution and military intervention involving France and the U.S. which was personified by Chirac versus Bush, and later Powell versus de Villepin, became a milestone in the U.S.–France relations.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anti-French propaganda exploiting Francophobic clichés immediately ensued in the U.S. and UK.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] A call for a boycott on French wine was launched in the U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The *New York Post* claimed that France had forgotten the American "sacrifice" in 1944 France.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] On 20 February 2003, British newspaper *The Sun* published a special issue entitled "Chirac is a worm", which said that "Chirac has become the shame of Europe".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] *The Guardian* wrote that both papers expressed the opinion of their owner, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Both supporters and opponents of the Iraq War widely viewed it within the context of a post–9/11 world, where the U.S. has sought to make terrorism the defining international security paradigm.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bush often described the war as a "central front in the war on terror".
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Some critics of the war, particularly within the U.S. military community, argued pointedly against the conflation of Iraq and the war on terror, and criticized Bush for losing focus on the more important objective of fighting al-Qaeda.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In an October 2002 speech, Retired Marine Gen.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anthony Zinni, former head of Central Command for U.S. forces in the Middle East and State Department's envoy to the Israeli–Palestinian conflict, called Iraq "maybe six or seven," in terms of U.S.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Middle East priorities, adding that "the affordability line may be drawn around five." However, while commander of CENTCOM, Zinni held a very different opinion concerning the threat posed by Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In testimony before the Senate Armed Services Committee in February 2000, Zinni said: "Iraq remains the most significant near-term threat to U.S. interests in the Persian Gulf region.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Besides arguing that Iraq was not the top strategic priority in the war on terrorism or in the Middle East, critics of the war also suggested that it could potentially destabilize the surrounding region.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Prominent among such critics was Brent Scowcroft, who served as National Security Advisor to George H.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In the opinion of Hayder al-Khoei, Iraq was already "destined for chaos" before 2003.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In a March 2003 Gallup poll, the day after the invasion, 76% of Americans supported the military action against Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In a March YouGov poll, 54% of Britons had approved of military action against Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] By 2007, opposition to the Iraq War had increased to 62% among Americans in a USA Today\Gallup poll.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2013, a Gallup poll found that 53 percent of Americans surveyed believed the Iraq War was a mistake.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] In 2023, an Axios/Ipsos poll found that 61% of Americans believed the U.S made a wrong decision by invading Iraq.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] This campaign featured a variety of new terminology, much of it initially coined by the U.S. government or military.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] The military official name for the invasion was Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Also notable was the usage "death squads" to refer to Fedayeen paramilitary forces.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Iraqi officials were given derogatory nicknames – e.g., "Chemical Ali" (Ali Hassan al-Majid), "Baghdad Bob" or "Comical Ali" (Muhammed Saeed al-Sahaf), and "Mrs.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Anthrax" or "Chemical Sally" (Huda Salih Mahdi Ammash).
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Many slogans and terms coined came to be used by Bush's political opponents, or those opposed to the war.
[src:bbc/2003-invasion-of-iraq-p04] Bush's press secretary Ari Fleischer talked about "Operation Iraqi Liberation" in a 2003 press briefing, and "Operation Iraqi Liberation (OIL)" was also used by David Rovics, a popular folk protest singer.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] The **2005 BBC strike** was a strike of more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC under the management of Mark Thompson.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] Much of the BBC's regular programming was affected, with many programmes being replaced with pre-recordings, and some being halted altogether, with those that remained suffering in quality due to the striking of many technical workers.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] The BBC was fragile, facing competition from other digital and cable broadcasting companies.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] The BBC is funded primarily by a television license and must convince the government to keep the license.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] At the time it needed to also convince the government to renew its government charter, which would expire the following year.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] The BBC was also facing conflict with the government at the time, after the BBC's unfavourable coverage of the Iraq War in 2003.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] An investigation led by Lord Hutton, a former judge, found that the BBC misrepresented the government's position on the war and engaged in sloppy reporting.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] Despite containing valid criticism of the BBC, the report was viewed by other sections of the media as an "establishment whitewash" – caused the BBC's chairman and director general to resign.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] Mark Thompson was appointed as the new BBC director to replace those who resigned.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] In order to restore the BBC's reputation and reform it for the digital age, he cut budgets by 15% across the board and removed 3,780 jobs.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] This would have saved about £355 million (US$642 million) to reinvest in new programmes.
[src:bbc/2005-bbc-strike] This caused anger across the BBC, and many workers went on strike.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The **British Broadcasting Corporation** (**BBC**) is a British public service broadcaster that serves as the primary national public broadcasting company of the United Kingdom, headquartered at Broadcasting House in London, England.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Originally established in 1922 as the British Broadcasting Company, it evolved into its current state with its current name on 1 January 1927.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It is the oldest and largest local and global broadcaster by stature and by number of employees, with a total staff of 21,000.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC was established under a royal charter, and operates under an agreement with the secretary of state for culture, media and sport.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Its work is funded principally by an annual television licence fee which is charged to all British households, companies, and organisations using any type of equipment to receive or record live television broadcasts or to use the BBC's streaming service, iPlayer.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The fee is set by the British government, agreed by Parliament, and is used to fund the BBC's radio, TV, and online services covering the nations and regions of the UK.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Since 1 April 2014, it has also funded the BBC World Service (launched in 1932 as the BBC Empire Service), which broadcasts in 43 languages as of 2026.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Some of the BBC's revenue comes from its commercial subsidiary BBC Studios (formerly BBC Worldwide), which sells BBC programs and services internationally and also distributes the BBC's international 24-hour English-language news services BBC News, and from BBC.com, provided by BBC Global News Ltd.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Since its formation on 18 October 1922, the BBC has played a prominent role in British life and culture.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It is sometimes informally referred to as **the Beeb** or **Auntie**.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1923 it launched *Radio Times* (subtitled "The official organ of the BBC"), the first broadcast listings magazine; the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11 million copies, the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Britain's first live public broadcast was made from the factory of Marconi Company in Chelmsford in June 1920.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It was sponsored by the *Daily Mail*'s Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe and featured the famous Australian soprano Dame Nellie Melba.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The Melba broadcast caught the people's imagination and marked a turning point in the British public's attitude to radio.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] However, this public enthusiasm was not shared in official circles where such broadcasts were held to interfere with important military and civil communications.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] By late 1920, the pressure from these quarters and uneasiness among the staff of the licensing authority, the General Post Office (GPO), was sufficient to lead to a ban on further Chelmsford broadcasts.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] But by 1922 the GPO had received nearly 100 broadcast licence requests and moved to rescind its ban in the wake of a petition by 63 wireless societies with over 3,000 members.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] John Reith, a Scottish Calvinist, was appointed its general manager in December 1922 a few weeks after the company made its first official broadcast.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Stanton Jefferies was its first director of music.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The company was to be financed by a royalty on the sale of BBC wireless receiving sets from approved domestic manufacturers.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] To this day, the BBC aims to follow the Reithian directive to "inform, educate and entertain".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The financial arrangements soon proved inadequate.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Set sales were disappointing as amateurs made their own receivers and listeners bought rival unlicensed sets.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] By mid-1923, discussions between the GPO and the BBC had become deadlocked and the Postmaster General commissioned a review of broadcasting by the Sykes Committee.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The committee recommended a short-term reorganisation of licence fees with improved enforcement to address the BBC's immediate financial distress, and an increased share of the licence revenue split between it and the GPO.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] This was to be followed by a simple 10 shillings licence fee to fund broadcasts.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC's broadcasting monopoly was made explicit for the duration of its current broadcast licence, as was the prohibition on advertising.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] To avoid competition with newspapers, Fleet Street persuaded the government to ban news bulletins before 7 pm and the BBC was required to source all news from external wire services.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The *Radio Times*, the world's first and longest-running radio and television listings magazine, was launched by Reith in September 1923.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The first edition, subtitled "The official organ of the BBC", was priced at tuppence (two pence) on newsstands, and quickly sold out its run of a quarter of a million copies.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Mid-1925 found the future of broadcasting under further consideration, this time by the Crawford committee.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] By now the BBC, under Reith's leadership, had forged a consensus favouring a continuation of the unified (monopoly) broadcasting service, but more money was still required to finance rapid expansion.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Wireless manufacturers were anxious to exit the loss-making consortium, and Reith was keen that the BBC be seen as a public service rather than a commercial enterprise.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The recommendations of the Crawford Committee were published in March the following year and were still under consideration by the GPO when the 1926 United Kingdom general strike broke out in May.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The strike temporarily interrupted newspaper production, and with restrictions on news bulletins waived, the BBC suddenly became the primary source of news for the duration of the crisis.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The crisis placed the BBC in a delicate position.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On the one hand Reith was acutely aware that the government might exercise its right to commandeer the BBC at any time as a mouthpiece of the government if the BBC were to step out of line, but on the other he was anxious to maintain public trust by appearing to be acting independently.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The government was divided on how to handle the BBC, but ended up trusting Reith, whose opposition to the strike mirrored the PM's own.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Although Winston Churchill in particular wanted to commandeer the BBC to use it "to the best possible advantage", Reith wrote that Stanley Baldwin's government wanted to be able to say "that they did not commandeer [the BBC], but they know that they can trust us not to be really impartial".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Thus the BBC was granted sufficient leeway to pursue the government's objectives largely in a manner of its own choosing.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Supporters of the strike nicknamed the BBC the BFC for British Falsehood Company.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Reith personally announced the end of the strike which he marked by reciting from Blake's "Jerusalem" signifying that England had been saved.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] While the BBC tends to characterise its coverage of the general strike by emphasising the positive impression created by its balanced coverage of the views of government and strikers, Seaton has characterised the episode as the invention of "modern propaganda in its British form".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Reith argued that trust gained by 'authentic impartial news' could then be used.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Impartial news was not necessarily an end in itself.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The British Broadcasting Corporation came into existence on 1 January 1927, and Reith – newly knighted – was appointed its first director general.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] To represent its purpose and (stated) values, the new corporation adopted the coat of arms, including the motto "Nation shall speak peace unto Nation".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] British radio audiences had little choice apart from BBC's programming approach.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Reith was viewed as taking a moralistic approach as an executive, aiming to broadcast "all that is best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement", and putting the programming in moral or ethical terms, advocating "a high moral tone" as "obviously of paramount importance".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Reith succeeded in building a high wall against a more tabloid, free-for-all in radio aimed at merely attracting the largest audience (and advertising revenue).
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] There was no paid advertising on the BBC; all the revenue came from a tax on receiving sets.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Highbrow audiences, however, greatly enjoyed it.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] At a time when American, Australian and Canadian stations were drawing huge audiences cheering for their local teams with the broadcast of baseball, rugby and hockey, the BBC emphasised service for a national rather than a regional audience.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Boat races were well covered along with tennis and horse racing, but the BBC was reluctant to spend its severely limited air time on long football or cricket games, regardless of their popularity.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] John Reith and the BBC, with support from the Crown, determined the universal needs of the people of Britain and broadcast content according to these perceived standards.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Reith effectively censored anything that he felt would be harmful, directly or indirectly.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] While recounting his time with the BBC in 1935, Raymond Postgate claims that BBC broadcasters were made to submit a draft of their potential broadcast for approval.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It was expected that they tailored their content to accommodate the modest, church-going elderly or a member of the Clergy.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Until 1928, entertainers broadcasting on the BBC, both singers and "talkers" were expected to avoid biblical quotations, Clerical impersonations and references, references to drink or Prohibition in the United States, vulgar and doubtful matter and political allusions.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC excluded popular foreign music and musicians from its broadcasts, while promoting British alternatives.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 5 March 1928, Stanley Baldwin, the Prime Minister, maintained the censorship of editorial opinions on public policy, but allowed the BBC to address matters of religious, political or industrial controversy.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The resulting political "talk series", designed to inform England on political issues, were criticised by members of parliament, including Winston Churchill, David Lloyd George and Sir Austen Chamberlain.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Those who opposed these chats claimed that they silence the opinions of those in Parliament who are not nominated by Party Leaders or Party Whips, thus stifling independent, non-official views.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In October 1932, the policemen of the Metropolitan Police Federation marched in protest at a proposed pay cut.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Fearing dissent within the police force and public support for the movement, the BBC censored its coverage of the events, only broadcasting official statements from the government.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Throughout the 1930s political broadcasts had been monitored by the BBC.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1935, the BBC censored the broadcasts of Oswald Mosley and Harry Pollitt.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Mosley was a leader of the British Union of Fascists, and Pollitt a leader of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] They were contracted to provide a series of five broadcasts on their parties' politics.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC, in conjunction with The Foreign Office of Britain, suspended this series and ultimately cancelled it without the notice of the public.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1938, Winston Churchill proposed a series of talks regarding British domestic and foreign politics and affairs but was censored.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The censorship of political discourse by the BBC started the shutdown of the political debate that manifested over the BBC's wartime airwaves.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The Foreign Office maintained that the public should not be aware of their role in the censorship.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] From 1935 to 1939, the BBC attempted to unite the British Empire's radio waves, sending staff to Egypt, Palestine, Newfoundland, Jamaica, India, Canada and South Africa.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Reith visited South Africa, lobbying for state-run radio programmes accepted by South African Parliament in 1936.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] A similar programme was adopted in Canada.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Through collaboration with these state-run broadcasting centres, Reith had an influence on the culture across the empire of Great Britain with his departure from the corporation in 1938.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Experimental television broadcasts were started in 1929 using an electromechanical 30-line system developed by John Logie Baird.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The superiority of the electronic system saw the mechanical system dropped early the following year, with the Marconi-EMI system the first fully electronic television system in the world to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The success of broadcasting provoked animosities between the BBC and well-established media such as theatres, concert halls and the recording industry.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] By 1929, the BBC complained that the agents of many comedians refused to sign contracts for broadcasting, because they feared it harmed the artist "by making his material stale" and that it "reduces the value of the artist as a visible music-hall performer".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Television broadcasting was suspended from 1 September 1939 to 7 June 1946, during World War II, and it was left to BBC Radio broadcasters such as Reginald Foort to keep the nation's spirits up.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC moved most of its radio operations out of London, initially to Bristol, and then to Bedford.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC employees during the war included George Orwell who spent two years with the broadcaster.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] During his role as prime minister during the war, Winston Churchill delivered 33 major wartime speeches by radio, all of which were carried by the BBC within the UK.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 18 June 1940, French general Charles de Gaulle, in exile in London as the leader of the Free French, made a speech, broadcast by the BBC, urging the French people not to capitulate to the Nazis.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In October 1940, Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret made their first radio broadcast for the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from cities.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1938 John Reith and the Government of the United Kingdom, specifically the Ministry of Information which had been set up for WWII, designed a censorship apparatus for the inevitability of war.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Due to the BBC's advancements in shortwave radio technology, the corporation could broadcast across the world during the Second World War.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Within Europe, the BBC European Service would gather intelligence and information regarding the current events of the war in English.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Regional BBC workers, based on their regional geo-political climate, would then further censor the material their broadcasts would cover.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Nothing was to be added outside the preordained news items.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] For example, the BBC Polish Service was heavily censored due to fears of jeopardising relations with the Soviet Union.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Controversial topics, i.e. the contested Polish and Soviet border, the deportation of Polish citizens, the arrests of Polish Home Army members and the Katyn massacre, were not included in Polish broadcasts.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] American radio broadcasts were broadcast across Europe on BBC channels.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] This material also passed through the BBC's censorship office, which surveilled and edited American coverage of British affairs.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] By 1940, across all BBC broadcasts, music by composers from enemy nations was censored.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In total, 99 German, 38 Austrian and 38 Italian composers were censored.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC argued that like the Italian or German languages, listeners would be irritated by the inclusion of enemy composers.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Any potential broadcasters said to have pacifist, communist or fascist ideologies were not allowed on the BBC's airwaves.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1937, a MI5 security officer was given a permanent office within the organisation.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] This officer would examine the files of potential political subversives and mark the files of those deemed a security risk to the organisation, blacklisting them.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] This was often done on spurious grounds; even so, the practice would continue and expand during the years of the Cold War.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] There was a widely reported urban myth that, upon resumption of the BBC television service after the war, announcer Leslie Mitchell started by saying, "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted ...".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In fact, the first person to appear when transmission resumed was Jasmine Bligh and the words said were, "Good afternoon, everybody.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Do you remember me, Jasmine Bligh...?" The European Broadcasting Union was formed on 12 February 1950, in Torquay with the BBC among the 23 founding broadcasting organizations.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Competition to the BBC was introduced in 1955, with the commercial and independently operated television network of Independent Television (ITV).
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] However, the BBC monopoly on radio services would persist until 8 October 1973 when under the control of the newly renamed Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), the UK's first Independent local radio station, LBC came on-air in the London area.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC2 used the higher resolution 625-line standard which had been standardised across Europe.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC2 was broadcast in colour from 1 July 1967 and was joined by BBC1 and ITV on 15 November 1969.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The 405-line VHF transmissions of BBC1 (and ITV) were continued for compatibility with older television receivers until 1985.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Starting in 1964, a series of pirate radio stations (starting with Radio Caroline) came on the air and forced the British government finally to regulate radio services to permit nationally based advertising-financed services.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In response, the BBC reorganised and renamed their radio channels.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 30 September 1967, the Light Programme was split into Radio 1 offering continuous "Popular" music and Radio 2 more "Easy Listening".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The "Third" programme became Radio 3 offering classical music and cultural programming.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The Home Service became Radio 4 offering news, and non-musical content such as quiz shows, readings, dramas and plays.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] As well as the four national channels, a series of local BBC radio stations were established in 1967, including Radio London.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1969, the BBC Enterprises department was formed to exploit BBC brands and programmes for commercial spin-off products.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1979, it became a wholly owned limited company, BBC Enterprises Ltd.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1974 the BBC's teletext service, Ceefax, was introduced, created initially to provide subtitling, but developed into a news and information service.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1978, BBC staff went on strike just before the Christmas, thus blocking out the transmission of both channels and amalgamating all four radio stations into one.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Since the deregulation of the UK television and radio market in the 1980s, the BBC has faced increased competition from the commercial sector (and from the advertiser-funded public service broadcaster Channel 4), especially on satellite television, cable television, and digital television services.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In the late 1980s, the BBC began a process of divestment by spinning off and selling parts of its organisation.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1988, it sold off the Hulton Press Library, a photographic archive which had been acquired from the *Picture Post* magazine by the BBC in 1957.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The archive was sold to Brian Deutsch and is now owned by Getty Images.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1987, the BBC decided to centralise its operations by the management team with the radio and television divisions joining forces together for the first time, the activities of the news and currents departments and coordinated jointly under the new directorate.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] During the 1990s, this process continued with the separation of certain operational arms of the corporation into autonomous but wholly owned subsidiaries, with the aim of generating additional revenue for programme-making.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC Enterprises was reorganised and relaunched in 1995, as BBC Worldwide Ltd.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1998, BBC studios, outside broadcasts, post production, design, costumes and wigs were spun off into BBC Resources Ltd.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC Research & Development has played a major part in the development of broadcasting and recording techniques.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC was also responsible for the development of the NICAM stereo standard.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The new station would be a news and sport station.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1997, BBC News 24, a rolling news channel, launched on digital television services, and the following year, BBC Choice was launched as the third general entertainment channel from the BBC.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC also purchased The Parliamentary Channel, which was renamed BBC Parliament.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1999, BBC Knowledge launched as a multimedia channel, with services available on the newly launched BBC Text digital teletext service (later rebranded as BBC Red Button), and on BBC Online.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The channel had an educational aim, which was modified later on in its life to offer documentaries.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2002 several television and radio channels were reorganised.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC Knowledge was replaced by BBC Four and became the BBC's arts and documentaries channel.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] CBBC, which had been a programming strand as Children's BBC since 1985, was split into CBBC and CBeebies, for younger children, with both new services getting a digital channel: the CBBC Channel and CBeebies Channel.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In addition to the television channels, new digital radio stations were created: 1Xtra, 6 Music and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC 1Xtra was a sister station to Radio 1 and specialised in modern black music, BBC 6 Music specialised in alternative music genres and BBC7 specialised in archive, speech and children's programming.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2008, another channel was launched, BBC Alba, a Scottish Gaelic service.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2006 BBC HD was launched as an experimental service, becoming official in December 2007.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The channel broadcast HD simulcasts of programmes on BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three and BBC Four as well as repeats of some older programmes in HD.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2010, an HD simulcast of BBC One launched: BBC One HD.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The channel uses HD versions of BBC One's schedule and uses upscaled versions of programmes not currently produced in HD.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC HD channel closed in March 2013 and was replaced by BBC Two HD in the same month.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The 2004 Hutton Inquiry and the subsequent report raised questions about the BBC's journalistic standards and its impartiality.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] This led to resignations of senior management members at the time including the then Director General, Greg Dyke.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In January 2007, the BBC released minutes of the board meeting which led to Greg Dyke's resignation.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC's IT, telephony and broadcast technology were brought together as BBC Technology Ltd in 2001, and the division was later sold to the German company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS).
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] SIS was subsequently acquired from Siemens by the French company Atos.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Further divestments included BBC Books (sold to Random House in 2006); BBC Outside Broadcasts Ltd (sold in 2008 to Satellite Information Services); Costumes and Wigs (stock sold in 2008 to Angels Costumes); and BBC Magazines (sold to Immediate Media Company in 2011).
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] After the sales of OBs and costumes, the remainder of BBC Resources was reorganised as BBC Studios and Post Production, which continues today as a wholly owned subsidiary of the BBC.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] A strike in May 2005 by more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC, disrupted much of the BBC's regular programming.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The blueprint for the future of the BBC resulting from the project was published ion 25 April 2006.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 18 October 2007, Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures", which included merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The plans included a reduction in posts of 2,500; including 1,800 redundancies, consolidating news operations, reducing programming output by 10% and selling off the flagship Television Centre building in London.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 20 October 2010 the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne announced that the television licence fee would be frozen at its current level until the end of the current charter in 2016.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The same announcement revealed that the BBC would take on the full cost of running the BBC World Service and the BBC Monitoring service from the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office, and partially finance the Welsh broadcaster S4C.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] BBC HD was closed on 26 March 2013, and replaced with an HD simulcast of BBC Two; however, flagship programmes, other channels and full funding for CBBC and CBeebies would be retained.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Numerous BBC facilities have been sold off, including New Broadcasting House on Wilmslow Road in Manchester.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Many major departments have been relocated to Broadcasting House in central London and MediaCityUK in Salford, particularly since the closure of BBC Television Centre in March 2013.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 16 February 2016, the BBC Three television service was discontinued and replaced by a digital outlet under the same name, targeting its young adult audience with web series and other content.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Under the new royal charter instituted in 2017, the corporation must publish an annual report to Ofcom, outlining its plans and public service obligations for the next year.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In its 2017–18 report, released July 2017, the BBC announced plans to "re-invent" its output to better compete against commercial streaming services such as Netflix.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Since 2017, the BBC has also funded the Local Democracy Reporting Service, with up to 165 journalists employed by independent news organisations to report on local democracy issues on a pooled basis.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2016 the BBC Director General Tony Hall announced a savings target of £800 million per year by 2021, which is about 23% of annual licence fee revenue.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Having to take on the £700 million cost for free TV licences for the over-75 pensioners, and rapid inflation in drama and sport coverage costs, was given as the reason.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Duplication of management and content spending would be reduced, and there would be a review of BBC News.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In September 2019 the BBC launched the Trusted News Initiative to work with news and social media companies to combat disinformation about national elections.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 520 staff reductions.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC's director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 2020, the BBC reported a £119 million deficit because of delays to cost reduction plans, and the forthcoming ending of the remaining £253 million funding towards pensioner licence fees would increase financial pressures.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In March 2023 the BBC was at the centre of a political row with football pundit Gary Lineker, after he criticised the British government's asylum policy on social media.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Lineker was suspended from his position on *Match of the Day* before being re-instated after receiving overwhelming support from his colleagues.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The scandal was made worse due to the connections between BBC's chairman, Richard Sharp, and the Conservative Party.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In April 2023 Richard Sharp resigned as chairman after a report found he did not disclose potential perceived conflicts of interest in his role in the facilitation of a loan to Prime Minister Boris Johnson.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Dame Elan Closs Stephens was appointed as acting chairwoman on 27 June 2023, and she would lead the BBC board for a year or until a new permanent chair has been appointed.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Samir Shah was subsequently appointed with effect from 4 March 2024.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In October 2024 it was announced that the BBC along with Sky Sports signed a deal to broadcast the 2025–26 season of the Women's Super League campaign.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In May 2025, BBC director general Tim Davie said there were plans to switch off traditional broadcast transmissions in the 2030s to transition to a fully online delivery of programmes.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In November 2025, following the leaking of a report that alleged systemic bias within the BBC, Tim Davie resigned as Director-General along with Deborah Turness as CEO of News within the organisation.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 16 December 2025, the UK government considered a green paper of new ways to fund the BBC, such as replacing the television licence with either advertising or a subscription model.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 25 March 2026, former Google executive Matt Brittin was appointed as the new Director-General.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] On 15 April 2026, BBC announced cuts up to 2,000 jobs—its largest layoffs in over a decade—to reduce costs by about 10% (around £500 million) over the next two years.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC is a chartered corporation, independent from direct government intervention, with its activities being overseen from April 2017 by the BBC Board and regulated by Ofcom.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC is a public broadcasting company that operates under a royal charter.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The charter is the constitutional basis for the BBC, and sets out the BBC's object, mission and public purposes.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It emphasises public service, (limited) editorial independence, prohibits advertising on domestic services and proclaims the BBC is to "seek to avoid adverse impacts on competition which are not necessary for the effective fulfilment of the Mission and the promotion of the Public Purposes".
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The charter additionally sets out that the BBC is subject to an additional agreement between it and the Culture Secretary, and that its operating licence is to be set by Ofcom, an external regulatory body.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It used to be that the Home Secretary be departmental to both the agreement as well as the licence, and regulatory duties fall to the BBC Trust, but the 2017 charter changed those 2007 arrangements.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The charter also outlines the BBC's governance and regulatory arrangements as a statutory corporation, including the role and composition of the BBC Board.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The current charter took effect on 1 January 2017 and is set to expire on 31 December 2027; the agreement being coterminous.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] It replaced the previous governing body, the BBC Trust, which itself had replaced the board of governors in 2007.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The board sets the strategy for the corporation, assesses the performance of the BBC's executive board in delivering the BBC's services, and appoints the director-general.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Ofcom is responsible for the regulation of the BBC.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Samir Shah has served as the chairman since 4 March 2024.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The executive committee is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the broadcaster.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Consisting of senior managers of the BBC, the committee meets once per month and is responsible for operational management and delivery of services within a framework set by the board, and is chaired by the director-general, who is chief executive and (from 1994) editor-in-chief.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] From as early as the 1930s until the 1990s, MI5, the British domestic intelligence service, engaged in the vetting of applicants for BBC jobs, a policy designed to keep out persons deemed subversive.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1933, BBC executive Colonel Alan Dawnay began to meet the head of MI5, Sir Vernon Kell, to informally trade information; from 1935, a formal arrangement was made whereby job applicants would be secretly vetted by MI5 for their political views (without their knowledge).
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] The BBC took up a policy of denying any suggestion by the press of such a relationship (the very existence of MI5 itself was not officially acknowledged until the Security Service Act 1989).
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] This relationship garnered wider public attention after an article by David Leigh and Paul Lashmar appeared in *The Observer* in August 1985, revealing that MI5 had been vetting appointments, running operations from Room 105 in Broadcasting House.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] At the time of the exposé, the operation was being run by Ronnie Stonham.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] A memo from 1984 revealed that blacklisted organisations included the far-left Communist Party of Great Britain, the Socialist Workers Party, the Workers Revolutionary Party and the Militant tendency, as well as the far-right National Front and the British National Party.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] An association with one of these groups could result in a denial of a job application.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In October 1985 the BBC announced that it would stop the vetting process, except for a few people in top roles, as well as those in charge of Wartime Broadcasting Service emergency broadcasting (in the event of a nuclear war) and staff of the BBC World Service.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] In 1990, following the Security Service Act 1989, vetting was further restricted to those responsible for wartime broadcasting and those with access to secret government information.
[src:bbc/bbc-p01] Michael Hodder, who succeeded Stonham, had the MI5 vetting files sent to the BBC Archives in Reading, Berkshire.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC has the second largest budget of any UK-based broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.722 billion in 2013/14 compared with £6.471 billion for Sky UK in 2013/14 and £1.843 billion for ITV in the calendar year 2013.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £169.50 per year per household as of April 2024.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Such a licence is required to legally receive broadcast television across the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] No licence is required to own a television used for other means, or for sound only radio sets (though a separate licence for these was also required for non-TV households until 1971).
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] A 50% discount is offered to people who are registered blind or severely visually impaired, and the licence is completely free for any household containing anyone aged 75 or over and receiving pension credit.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC pursues its licence fee collection and enforcement under the trading name "TV Licensing".
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The revenue is collected privately by Capita, an outside agency, and is paid into the central government Consolidated Fund, a process defined in the Communications Act 2003.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Funds are then allocated by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75-year-olds.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The licence fee is classified as a tax, and its evasion is a criminal offence.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Since 1991, collection and enforcement of the licence fee has been the responsibility of the BBC in its role as TV Licensing Authority.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC carries out surveillance (mostly using subcontractors) on properties (under the auspices of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000) and may conduct searches of a property using a search warrant.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] According to TV Licensing, 216,900 people in the UK were caught watching TV without a licence in 2018/19.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Licence fee evasion makes up about one-tenth of all cases prosecuted in magistrates' courts, representing 0.3% of court time.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years, with BBC Worldwide contributing some £243 million to the BBC's core public service business.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] But the licence fee has attracted criticism.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] It has been argued that in an age of multi-stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC's use of private sector company Capita to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC uses advertising campaigns to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Past campaigns have been criticised by Conservative MP Boris Johnson and former MP Ann Widdecombe for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] In 2023, about half a million UK households cancelled their TV licence, driven by shifting viewing habits and financial pressures.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] As a result, the BBC saw a decline in revenue, with the number of households paying the licence fee dropping to 23.9 million.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The majority of the BBC's commercial output comes from its commercial arm BBC Worldwide which sell programmes abroad and exploit key brands for merchandise.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] In April 2026, the BBC announced that they would be cutting between 1,800 and 2,000 jobs, citing a need to save £500 million over the coming two years.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House in Portland Place, central London, is the official headquarters of the BBC.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] It is also the home of BBC News, which relocated to the building from BBC Television Centre in 2013.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] On the front of the building are statues of Prospero and Ariel, characters from William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest*, sculpted by Eric Gill.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Renovation of Broadcasting House began in 2002, and was completed in 2012.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Until it closed at the end of March 2013, BBC Television was based at Television Centre, a purpose-built television facility opened in 1960 located in White City, four miles (6 km) west of central London.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] This facility was host to a number of famous guests and programmes through the years, and its name and image is familiar with many British citizens.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Nearby, the White City Place complex contains numerous programme offices, housed in Centre House, the Media Centre and Broadcast Centre.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] It is in this area around Shepherd's Bush that the majority of BBC employees worked.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] As part of a major reorganisation of BBC property, the entire BBC News operation relocated from the News Centre at BBC Television Centre to the refurbished Broadcasting House to create what is being described as "one of the world's largest live broadcast centres".
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC News Channel and BBC News International relocated to the premises in early 2013.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House is now also home to most of the BBC's national radio stations, and the BBC World Service.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The major part of this plan involved the demolition of the two post-war extensions to the building and construction of an extension designed by Sir Richard MacCormac of MJP Architects.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] This move concentrated the BBC's London operations, allowing them to sell Television Centre.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] As well as the two main sites in London (Broadcasting House and White City), there are seven other important BBC production centres in the UK, mainly specialising in different productions.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Cardiff is home to BBC Cymru Wales, which specialises in drama production.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Open since 2012, and containing 7 new studios, Roath Lock is notable as the home of productions such as *Doctor Who* and *Casualty*.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House Belfast, home to BBC Northern Ireland, specialises in original drama and comedy, and has taken part in many co-productions with independent companies and notably with RTÉ in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] BBC Scotland, based in Pacific Quay, Glasgow is a large producer of programmes for the network, including several quiz shows.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] In England, the larger regions also produce some programming.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Previously the largest hub of BBC programming from the regions had been BBC North West.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] At present they produce all religious and ethical programmes on the BBC, as well as other programmes such as *A Question of Sport*.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] However, this is to be merged and expanded under the BBC North project, which involved the region moving from New Broadcasting House, Manchester, to MediaCityUK.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] BBC Midlands, based at Mailbox Birmingham, also produces drama and contains the headquarters for the English regions and the BBC's daytime output.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Other production centres include Broadcasting House Bristol, home of BBC West and famously the BBC Studios Natural History Unit and to a lesser extent, Quarry Hill in Leeds, home of BBC Yorkshire.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] There are also many smaller local and regional studios throughout the UK, operating the BBC regional television services and the BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates several news gathering centres in various locations around the world, which provide news coverage of that region to the national and international news operations.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] In 2004 the BBC contracted out its former BBC Technology division to the German engineering and electronics company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS), outsourcing its IT, telephony and broadcast technology systems.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] When Atos Origin acquired the SIS division from Siemens in December 2010 for €850 million (£720m), the BBC support contract also passed to Atos, and in July 2011, the BBC announced to staff that its technology support would become an Atos service.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] Siemens staff working on the BBC contract were transferred to Atos; the BBC's Information Technology systems are now managed by Atos.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] In 2012, the BBC's then-chief technology officer John Linwood, expressed confidence in service improvements to the BBC's technology provision brought about by Atos.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] He also stated that supplier accountability had been strengthened following some high-profile technology failures which had taken place during the partnership with Siemens.
[src:bbc/bbc-p02] The BBC operates several television channels nationally and internationally.
